WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.240
[Amit Varma]: Are you a proud Indian? I will answer that question this way. I love my country and I

00:00:10.240 --> 00:00:15.560
[Amit Varma]: certainly count myself as patriotic. I think it is irrational to feel pride at anything

00:00:15.560 --> 00:00:19.560
[Amit Varma]: other than one's own achievements. And even that may be irrational given that free will

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:25.600
[Amit Varma]: may be an illusion. Despite this, I do feel a tinge of irrational patriotic pride sometimes,

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:29.600
[Amit Varma]: such as when Vishy Anand plays a beautiful game of chess, or Jasprit Bhoomra takes another

00:00:29.600 --> 00:00:35.400
[Amit Varma]: international wicket with an unplayable delivery. Now, if you do recognize pride as a legitimate

00:00:35.400 --> 00:00:41.680
[Amit Varma]: emotion in a national context, then it's fair also to recognize the other side of that coin,

00:00:41.680 --> 00:00:48.560
[Amit Varma]: shame. And that brings up the question, should we not be ashamed that after 72 years of independence,

00:00:48.560 --> 00:00:53.760
[Amit Varma]: so much of this country still struggles to put food on the plate. So many of us live

00:00:53.760 --> 00:00:59.480
[Amit Varma]: in the 19th century, while a few elites live in the 21st. And that misogyny and identarian

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:05.160
[Amit Varma]: divisions continue to tear us apart. A country with our wealth of natural resources, and

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:09.640
[Amit Varma]: by that I mean our people, should have become a developed economy by now, with citizens

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:14.800
[Amit Varma]: who are comfortable in their skin and confident of their place in the world, instead of carrying

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:20.440
[Amit Varma]: so much baggage from a partly imaginary past. Although I think our nation is at a specific

00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:25.080
[Amit Varma]: crisis point today, I will not blame this just on the party in charge right now. Our

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:29.960
[Amit Varma]: current ruptures are like a cardiac arrest suffered by a patient with terminal cancer

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:35.120
[Amit Varma]: and chronic diabetes. We have been afflicted for all 72 years of our existence, and we

00:01:35.120 --> 00:01:40.840
[Amit Varma]: owe it to ourselves to face up to our afflictions. We cannot do it by creating binaries today

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:46.760
[Amit Varma]: or one party good, another party bad. I often say that the BJP behaves as if history ended

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:51.640
[Amit Varma]: at 2014. And they should not be held responsible for what has happened since. The Congress

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:57.000
[Amit Varma]: behaves as if history began at 2014, as if the decades of misgovernance had not ravaged

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:02.520
[Amit Varma]: this nation before that. If we want to recover as a nation and actually give ourselves reasons

00:02:02.520 --> 00:02:08.720
[Amit Varma]: to be proud Indians, we must look inward with a critical eye. So much that goes wrong gets

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:14.240
[Amit Varma]: normalized so fast, we must tear away that layer of normalization and be outraged again

00:02:14.240 --> 00:02:19.640
[Amit Varma]: and be outraged constantly and collectively. Outrage is not just our privilege as Indian

00:02:19.640 --> 00:02:27.920
[Unknown]: citizens. It is our duty. Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly

00:02:27.920 --> 00:02:33.920
[Unknown]: podcast on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Badma.

00:02:33.920 --> 00:02:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Kapil Komi Reddy, whose excellent

00:02:40.240 --> 00:02:45.720
[Amit Varma]: book Malevolent Republic brims with informed outrage. And reading it, I began questioning

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:51.160
[Amit Varma]: myself why am I not angrier? As all listeners of this show would know, I am usually outraged

00:02:51.160 --> 00:02:56.480
[Amit Varma]: enough for all of us. Kapil's book casts a merciless eye over all of Indian politics

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:02.560
[Amit Varma]: with no corner left untouched. He takes no prisoners. But before we begin our conversation,

00:03:02.560 --> 00:03:08.480
[Amit Varma]: let's take a quick commercial break. If you're listening to the scene and the unseen,

00:03:08.480 --> 00:03:12.920
[Amit Varma]: it means you like listening to audio and you're thirsty for knowledge. That being the case,

