[Amit Varma]: all I'll say about it. Fascism by Madeleine Albright on Storytel. Download their app or

00:04:06.240 --> 00:04:13.000
[Amit Varma]: visit Storytel.com. Remember, it is Storytel with a single l, Storytel.com. Kapil, welcome

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.840
[Amit Varma]: to the show. Thank you for having me, Amit. Kapil, before we sort of begin talking about

00:04:17.840 --> 00:04:22.160
[Amit Varma]: the book and so on, tell me a bit about your personal journey, which in a sense is salient

00:04:22.160 --> 00:04:26.880
[Amit Varma]: because your book also connects the personal with the political. So where did you grow

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:32.920
[Guest]: up? Where did you get educated? Who were your early influences? So I had a, as I write about

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:38.880
[Guest]: my upbringing in my book, I grew up in Hyderabad. I was born there and I was sent at a young

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:46.000
[Guest]: age to a madrasa, an Islamic seminary, because my father decided that an exposure of that

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:51.760
[Guest]: kind would inoculate me in later life against sectarian temptations. His own family had

00:04:51.760 --> 00:04:57.440
[Guest]: suffered during the partition. Not a lot of people know this, but we seem to think that

00:04:57.440 --> 00:05:03.560
[Guest]: South India didn't suffer the ravages of partition. That's not true. Hyderabad was singed by the

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:08.440
[Guest]: furies of partition and my family were among those who suffered, who were exposed to those

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:15.800
[Guest]: furies. And my father's politics were in some sense a reaction to that. So he enrolled me

00:05:15.800 --> 00:05:22.040
[Guest]: at a madrasa where I spent some time and I didn't have reasons to look back on that upbringing

00:05:22.040 --> 00:05:28.040
[Guest]: with much fondness or nostalgia because I was shipped out of Hyderabad. I was sent to

00:05:28.040 --> 00:05:32.680
[Guest]: Northern India. I went to a boarding school and then I sort of travelled around India

00:05:32.680 --> 00:05:38.280
[Guest]: from place to place, hopping from school to school. When I reflect on that childhood,

00:05:38.280 --> 00:05:43.800
[Guest]: it's so strange because there are so many fragments that do not fit into a whole. And

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:51.080
[Guest]: then in my teenage years, I went away to England. Then I came back to India later and I met

00:05:51.080 --> 00:06:00.040
[Guest]: a childhood friend from my time at the madrasa and his life was, had taken such a drastic

00:06:00.040 --> 00:06:08.520
[Guest]: turn from my own. He'd been exposed to the roughest edges of the Indian state and reflecting

00:06:08.520 --> 00:06:18.160
[Guest]: on how he experienced India and how I experienced India made me arrive at, made me question

00:06:18.160 --> 00:06:25.200
[Guest]: many of my assumptions about Indianness because for someone of my background, being born Indian

00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:30.200
[Guest]: is a source of, being Indian is a source of tremendous pride. You think of India as this

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:36.040
[Guest]: exceptional entity, but for him, India meant none of those things. And it forced me to

00:06:36.040 --> 00:06:39.760
[Guest]: reckon with my own understanding of India. And that's why I began the book the way I

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:42.120
[Amit Varma]: did without personal reflection.

00:06:42.120 --> 00:06:47.360
[Amit Varma]: And it kind of strikes me that part of that personal reflection also is that you are shaped

00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:52.400
[Amit Varma]: by, you know, the circumstances that took you wherever they took you. And Murad, your

00:06:52.400 --> 00:06:57.720
[Amit Varma]: friend is also shaped by the circumstances that he was sort of in. And, you know, one

00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:03.120
[Amit Varma]: of the sort of larger questions that kind of struck me when I was reading that part

00:07:03.120 --> 00:07:09.040
[Amit Varma]: of the book is about how much of our beliefs are shaped by our circumstance. You know,

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:13.120
[Amit Varma]: and I say this not just about the ordinary person, not just about you or me who have

00:07:13.120 --> 00:07:18.840
[Amit Varma]: had, you know, different kinds of very privileged upbringings, but also when we sort of look

00:07:18.840 --> 00:07:22.960
[Amit Varma]: back on our leaders, like recently, for example, there were two interesting biographies of

00:07:22.960 --> 00:07:30.000
[Amit Varma]: Veer Savarkar by Vikram Sampath and Vaibhav Purandhare. And, you know, reading them also

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:35.480
[Amit Varma]: led me to his present diaries. Now, Savarkar's thinking is something that I absolutely loathe,

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:39.500
[Amit Varma]: obviously, you know, Hindutva is a horrible, horrible book. But the interesting thing is,

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:44.120
[Amit Varma]: one of the things I realized in that book was that till about 1910, you know, Savarkar

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:47.680
[Amit Varma]: believed that Hindus and Muslims together had a place in India, that they were both

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:51.520
[Amit Varma]: part of this nation. And then he spent all those years in the Andamans where he suffered

00:07:51.520 --> 00:07:58.240
[Amit Varma]: terrible torture. And a lot of the intermediaries between the British jailers and him were this

00:07:58.240 --> 00:08:06.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of class of Muslim jailers, you know, Pathans and so on. And the torture he suffered

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:11.700
[Amit Varma]: at their hands radicalized him and made him incredibly anti-Muslim. And there was a case

00:08:11.700 --> 00:08:17.520
[Amit Varma]: of sort of how circumstance radicalized one man and changed his thinking in such a way

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:22.000
[Amit Varma]: that he then writes a book and that book then shapes a cultural movement. And suddenly all

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:27.560
[Amit Varma]: of that is at the center of everything today. And I don't mean this as apology for Savarkar

00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:32.720
[Amit Varma]: in any way. I think of him as vastly as a negative figure. And the ideology that he

00:08:32.720 --> 00:08:37.400
[Amit Varma]: played a part in fomenting is, of course, hurting our country today, as you write about

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:42.920
[Amit Varma]: so eloquently in your book. But circumstances do play a big role. For example, Ram Guha

00:08:42.920 --> 00:08:47.440
[Amit Varma]: talks about how Mahatma Gandhi, you know, Mohandas Gandhi comes back from London and

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:53.160
[Amit Varma]: is unable to really hold down a job in Bombay. So he goes to South Africa, where perforce

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:58.560
[Amit Varma]: he is employed by Muslims and he has to work with them. And, you know, he faces colonial

00:08:58.560 --> 00:09:04.760
[Amit Varma]: injustice and also later on in his movement as the Satyagrahas go on, he cannot get by

00:09:04.760 --> 00:09:10.040
[Amit Varma]: without the support of the relatively lower class Tamils, who are also in South Africa

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:16.720
[Amit Varma]: and therefore, so again, you see how Gandhi's syncretic vision is shaped by circumstance

00:09:16.720 --> 00:09:21.360
[Amit Varma]: and Savarkar's radicalism is shaped by circumstance. And it also strikes me and maybe I'm rambling

00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:28.120
[Amit Varma]: here but that this can lead to vicious circles of a kind. And what are your thoughts on that?

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:33.960
[Guest]: That is extremely fascinating. When you were saying that, one of the things I was thinking

00:09:33.960 --> 00:09:41.360
[Guest]: is the parallel between Savarkar and Jinnah. One of the excuses proffered for Jinnah is

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:47.700
[Guest]: that he was a good man who was damaged by the conduct of the Congress Party and then

00:09:47.700 --> 00:09:54.000
[Guest]: decided to retaliate in the manner he did. And it's true that if you look back on Savarkar's

00:09:54.000 --> 00:10:00.400
[Guest]: history of the mutiny or the great rebellion, you see shards of hope in that. You see him

00:10:00.400 --> 00:10:06.960
[Guest]: write about Hindu-Muslim unity, a kind of unity forged in opposition to British occupiers.

00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:12.560
[Guest]: There are still elements of resentment there, self-hatred there, but there's also hope there.

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:18.480
[Guest]: And as you say, his experience of prison completely destroyed the remnants of humanity within

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:24.400
[Guest]: him. There's a fascinating paper by Ashish Nandy, the parallels between Savarkar and

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:31.840
[Guest]: Jinnah. Jinnah is radicalised during his time, during his interaction with the Congress Party.

00:10:31.840 --> 00:10:39.560
[Guest]: He leaves for England in 1931. In 1929, his young wife is dead. In 1931, he goes to England.

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:45.200
[Guest]: By the time he comes back, he's a completely different man. He no longer believes in Hindu-Muslim

00:10:45.200 --> 00:10:56.280
[Guest]: unity. He sees Muslims as a distinct people. It is the experience of bigotry, of being

00:10:56.280 --> 00:11:04.840
[Guest]: treated as a lesser creature by people you think of as your equals that prompts him to

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:11.200
[Guest]: discard everything he held onto in his previous life. And that's the case with Savarkar too.

00:11:11.200 --> 00:11:14.960
[Guest]: A lot of us are shaped by our circumstances, that's true, but it's important to mention

00:11:14.960 --> 00:11:21.760
[Guest]: here that your misery doesn't confer upon you the right to inflict suffering on other

00:11:21.760 --> 00:11:28.240
[Guest]: people. And what Savarkar did is he became an extremely sadistic human being in his later

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:36.560
[Guest]: life. He wrote prescriptions for Hindus to torture Muslims. He wanted bodies of Muslim

00:11:36.560 --> 00:11:41.960
[Guest]: women exhumed and molested. He wanted tit-for-tat retaliation. He wanted Indian soldiers to

00:11:41.960 --> 00:11:48.480
[Guest]: go and molest Pakistani women. And when his wife died, he couldn't even bring himself

00:11:48.480 --> 00:11:58.600
[Guest]: to weep. His humanity had almost evaporated. And that is the tragedy of psychological trauma,

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:03.640
[Guest]: psychological damage. And there's something eerily similar about Savarkar and Jinnah.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:09.120
[Guest]: They're so alike, the two men. Jinnah is often put in the same camp as Gandhi and Nehru.

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:12.680
[Guest]: Jinnah really belongs in the same pantheon as Savarkar.

00:12:12.680 --> 00:12:19.200
[Amit Varma]: I would actually say that, you know, till maybe around 1920-21, Jinnah is one of the

00:12:19.200 --> 00:12:24.200
[Amit Varma]: great moderates. You know, Jinnah was part of a band with, you know, Gokhale and Ferozia

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:28.720
[Amit Varma]: Mehta and all of those and Gandhi looked up to Gokhale enormously. And what happens is

00:12:28.720 --> 00:12:34.760
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi comes back from South Africa, Gokhale dies soon after. But, you know, Gokhale has

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:38.960
[Amit Varma]: read Hind Swaraj, Gokhale has spoken to Gandhi. He knows that Gandhi is anything but a moderate

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:44.520
[Amit Varma]: in that sense. He's sort of all over the place. He's like a black swan event in terms of ideology.

00:12:44.520 --> 00:12:48.320
[Amit Varma]: And Gokhale's advice to Gandhi, obviously, is just don't enter politics now, travel the

00:12:48.320 --> 00:12:52.480
[Amit Varma]: country for a year, which he dutifully does. Though after Gokhale dies as a tribute, he

00:12:52.480 --> 00:12:56.280
[Amit Varma]: does it without wearing his shoes, I think, which is slightly weird. And then, you know,

00:12:56.280 --> 00:13:00.040
[Amit Varma]: he tries to make a mark at the Congress. The first time he's there, I think 1918 or whatever,

00:13:00.040 --> 00:13:06.440
[Amit Varma]: he fails utterly. But then the Khilafat movement happens. And Jinnah finds this extremely incongruous

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:13.320
[Amit Varma]: and incoherent that you have a demand for this larger Muslim ummah tied together with

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:18.040
[Amit Varma]: this quest for Indian nationhood. And this coming together doesn't make sense to him.

00:13:18.040 --> 00:13:23.160
[Amit Varma]: But this coming together is a willing or unwilling tactical ploy, which allows Gandhi to take

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:26.560
[Amit Varma]: over the Congress Party and Jinnah walks out in disgust and says, I will never have anything

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:31.760
[Amit Varma]: to do with this again. And it's very interesting that how then this person who was until then

00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:36.920
[Amit Varma]: a great moderate leader, suddenly then goes off into this different direction driven by

00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:41.320
[Amit Varma]: circumstances and you have a very good quote in your book by Lincoln, which you sort of

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:46.440
[Amit Varma]: Distinction will be his paramount objective. Yeah, where I'll just go that you say quote,

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:51.560
[Amit Varma]: where Lincoln was warning against, you know, demagogues of a particular sort, and obviously

00:13:51.560 --> 00:13:56.280
[Amit Varma]: not Jinnah at that time, because what would he know? And he said, quote, distinction will

00:13:56.280 --> 00:14:01.440
[Amit Varma]: be his paramount object. And although he would as willingly perhaps more so acquire it by

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:06.360
[Amit Varma]: doing good as harm, that opportunity being passed, and nothing left to be done in the

00:14:06.360 --> 00:14:11.880
[Amit Varma]: way of building up, he would set boldly to the task of pulling down, stop quote. And

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:16.560
[Amit Varma]: there are a lot of fascinating counterfactuals here where, you know, if the black swan event

00:14:16.560 --> 00:14:21.240
[Amit Varma]: of Gandhi doesn't happen, then Jinnah is probably a great moderate leader. And we remember Jinnah

00:14:21.240 --> 00:14:25.720
[Guest]: is a man ahead of his times. Jinnah, the first election Jinnah fights is against a Muslim

00:14:25.720 --> 00:14:30.080
[Guest]: League candidate. And Jinnah goes about telling Muslims that you know, the idea of Hindu Muslim

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:36.800
[Guest]: disunity, enmity, animosity, is a bogey invented by the British to divide you. Jinnah is the

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:42.200
[Guest]: kind of guy who wants to outgrow his religious identity, and fuse himself into the Indian

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:47.760
[Guest]: identity, a broad Indian identity, and he wants to create a pan Indian identity. And

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:55.000
[Guest]: he, when Gandhi comes, his ambitions are thwarted. Gokhale, his great mentor dies, and Gandhi

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:05.440
[Guest]: just seizes the nationalist movement by mobilizing people around religious unity created by appealing

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:10.360
[Guest]: to their worst instincts. That is completely antithetical to everything Jinnah believes

00:15:10.360 --> 00:15:14.520
[Guest]: in. The other person that it alienates is Savarkar. Savarkar is also appalled by it

00:15:14.520 --> 00:15:19.400
[Guest]: because Savarkar believes subsequently that this is a kind of bribe to the fundamentalist

00:15:19.400 --> 00:15:25.480
[Guest]: Muslims. Jinnah believes that this will create monsters that we will not be able to slay.

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:30.720
[Guest]: Were they both right? They were both right. Of course, they were both right. But the radicalizing

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:35.800
[Guest]: movement Jinnah obviously feels that, you know, here I am an Indian, who is this interloper

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:40.240
[Guest]: coming from South Africa and telling me and sidelining me. Jinnah has every right to feel

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:46.560
[Guest]: that resentment. Savarkar and Jinnah then take a very radical turn, as you know, the

00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:52.280
[Guest]: radicalizing movement for Hindu nationalists is the Mughla Massacre. And the failure of

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:56.920
[Guest]: the Congress Party to adequately condemn that, to forcefully condemn that, because the Congress

00:15:56.920 --> 00:16:01.120
[Guest]: Party has entered into an alliance with the most fundamentalist faction of the Muslim

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:07.680
[Guest]: community. And Hindu Mahasabha feel that Congress is not really, much like Jinnah feels that,

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:13.360
[Guest]: you know, Congress is now beholden to religious interests, not to national interests. And

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:18.360
[Guest]: Hindu Mahasabha progressively detaches from the Congress Party. And Savarkar's book is

00:16:18.360 --> 00:16:24.240
[Guest]: actually read by Heghewar in 1923 in manuscript form. And Heghewar is a lifelong Congress member.

00:16:24.240 --> 00:16:32.040
[Guest]: And he founds the RSS in 1925. And Jinnah also detaches himself, is disgusted, frankly,

00:16:32.040 --> 00:16:35.920
[Guest]: by everything the Congress Party is becoming under Mahatma Gandhi, or Gandhi at that stage,

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:40.880
[Guest]: he won't call him Mahatma. And there is a remarkable similarity between the two sides.

00:16:40.880 --> 00:16:46.000
[Guest]: And they're both right, obviously, for different reasons. Jinnah is appalled that Mahatma that

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:53.320
[Guest]: Gandhi is legitimizing the most extreme segments of the Muslim community. And the Hindu nationalists

00:16:53.320 --> 00:16:55.480
[Guest]: are also appalled for the very same reason.

00:16:55.480 --> 00:17:00.920
[Amit Varma]: No, it's really interesting. And like you said, the Hindu Mahasabha was almost a faction

00:17:00.920 --> 00:17:05.520
[Amit Varma]: of the Congress in the sense that it was an interest group, it was almost a cultural thing

00:17:05.520 --> 00:17:11.200
[Amit Varma]: more than a political thing. One of its pioneers was Lala Lajpat Rai. So, and then subsequently

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:17.080
[Amit Varma]: over the decades, it got radicalized. What is also happening here, this interesting parallel

00:17:17.080 --> 00:17:21.360
[Amit Varma]: movement, which, this is brilliant book by Akshay Mukul called The Founding of the Gita

00:17:21.360 --> 00:17:26.640
[Amit Varma]: Press, which sort of explodes, right, and I had a great episode with him. And what also

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:33.480
[Amit Varma]: sort of begins to happen here is that you find other forces, for example, other impetuses,

00:17:33.480 --> 00:17:40.280
[Amit Varma]: that is newly rich Marwari businessmen in Calcutta now decide that we want to sort of

00:17:40.280 --> 00:17:45.960
[Amit Varma]: rise up the ladder in terms of status and whatever. And, you know, Akshay speaks very

00:17:45.960 --> 00:17:51.440
[Amit Varma]: interestingly of how the earlier sort of partnership between the Kshatriyas and the Brahmins sort

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:56.560
[Amit Varma]: of now changes as the Marwaris insert themselves. And one of the ways in which they do this

00:17:56.560 --> 00:18:01.520
[Amit Varma]: is by funding the Gita Press and funding a lot of the Hindu nationalist movement. And

00:18:01.520 --> 00:18:05.760
[Amit Varma]: what I found remarkable about his book, and which should not have been an eye opener to

00:18:05.760 --> 00:18:14.720
[Amit Varma]: me, but was, is that there was this profoundly strong cultural movement that was building

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:20.000
[Amit Varma]: up from the 20s, which was planned, which had enormous impetus, like we often look at

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:25.040
[Amit Varma]: Hindutva quite correctly, as not really an Indian ideology, it's inspired by European

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:30.640
[Amit Varma]: fascism and, you know, that kind of nationalism, which, you know, wasn't sort of ingrained

00:18:30.640 --> 00:18:36.160
[Amit Varma]: in India. So in that sense, a political ideology, yes, is inspired by all of that. But there's

00:18:36.160 --> 00:18:40.440
[Amit Varma]: also a cultural movement gradually building up, building up, building up. And in some

00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:46.040
[Amit Varma]: ways, it could be argued that the politics has today finally caught up with culture.

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:47.040
[Guest]: What are your views on that?

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:51.640
[Guest]: There were multiple strands to the what we now call Hindu nationalism. If you look at

00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:56.920
[Guest]: the RSS's founding charter, it is explicitly anti-fascistic, actually, because it has rules

00:18:56.920 --> 00:19:03.800
[Guest]: against personality cults. And it seeks to emancipate the individual from the bane of

00:19:03.800 --> 00:19:09.000
[Guest]: caste. And in pre-independence India, the RSS playgrounds were one of the few places

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:14.320
[Guest]: where people of different castes would come together, because caste was seen as the dividing

00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:20.400
[Guest]: instrument, the thing that divided Indians and enabled foreigners to conquer India so

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:26.560
[Guest]: swiftly was because Indians, Hindus were divided by caste. So RSS in that sense was quite radical

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:27.560
[Amit Varma]: in its outlook.

00:19:27.560 --> 00:19:29.280
[Amit Varma]: In fact, even Savarkar was very anti-caste.

00:19:29.280 --> 00:19:33.800
[Guest]: Savarkar was extremely anti-caste. Again, one of the parallels with Jinnah is that neither

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:39.040
[Guest]: of them, you know, were really believers in the faith around which they mobilized people.

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:43.440
[Guest]: But there were different strands. As you said, there was a cultural strand, there was a political

00:19:43.440 --> 00:19:48.720
[Guest]: strand, there was a militant strand, all of them fused. And there was no particular design

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:53.480
[Guest]: behind the fusion. They just came together because of the chaos and tumult of India's

00:19:53.480 --> 00:20:01.400
[Guest]: political scene at the time. And the blend of that created mixing with the resentments

00:20:01.400 --> 00:20:04.000
[Guest]: fostered by the partition of India.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:10.520
[Guest]: Remember that Hindu nationalism did not have an audience beyond upper caste men for a very

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:17.120
[Guest]: long time. Hindu Mahasabha was electorally, you know, it didn't perform very well electorally.

00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:22.940
[Guest]: The audience for that argument really came into existence after partition, because once

00:20:22.940 --> 00:20:28.500
[Guest]: a state had been created for India's Muslims, the argument went that what remained was going

00:20:28.500 --> 00:20:34.580
[Guest]: to be the state for Indian Hindus. It's Nehru and the Congress Party that stopped them from

00:20:34.580 --> 00:20:40.960
[Guest]: seizing power, that banished them from the centers of power. But culturally, those resentments

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:46.640
[Guest]: brewed precisely because they were not offered a seat at the table. They were able to mobilize

00:20:46.640 --> 00:20:52.760
[Guest]: people from the ground up. These propagandists went to every village, every town in India,

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:59.440
[Guest]: and they patiently worked for years. They would go into villages. They created a brotherhood,

00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:06.000
[Guest]: an ideological brotherhood, whose power we only realized in the 80s. So Indian society

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:13.440
[Guest]: had become immersed in this alternative world, which the political world wasn't really aware

00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:21.520
[Guest]: of. And when the two sides caught up, the dissolution of the secular state was very

00:21:21.520 --> 00:21:22.520
[Amit Varma]: rapid.

00:21:22.520 --> 00:21:28.480
[Amit Varma]: So I have sort of three responses to this third question. One response is that I would

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:33.640
[Amit Varma]: hold that the cultural movement that led to Hindu nationalism, so to say, was not something

00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:37.940
[Amit Varma]: that really, you know, began after partition or was driven by the propagandists of the

00:21:37.940 --> 00:21:42.800
[Amit Varma]: RSS and so on. It was like, you know, as the history of the Gita Press shows, it was alive

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:48.840
[Amit Varma]: and throbbing even before that. My second observation would be that when we look back

00:21:48.840 --> 00:21:53.400
[Amit Varma]: at Hindu nationalism, I think it might be a mistake just to look at groups like the

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:58.320
[Amit Varma]: RSS and the Hindu Mahasabha, because there was a strong strand of Hindu nationalism very

00:21:58.320 --> 00:22:02.840
[Amit Varma]: different from the Hindutva nationalism of today, which was within the Congress itself.

00:22:02.840 --> 00:22:07.940
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, you know, right from Madan Mohan Malviya, Lala Lajpat Rai, and even at the time of independence,

00:22:07.940 --> 00:22:13.440
[Amit Varma]: you had Patel, Pant, Prasad, even later on Lal Bahadur Shastri and Gulzari Lal Nanda,

00:22:13.440 --> 00:22:19.280
[Amit Varma]: who was one of the founders of the VHP. And my question, therefore, is a dual question.

00:22:19.280 --> 00:22:26.200
[Amit Varma]: One is that, is it a remarkable accident of history that it happens to be Nehru, who was

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:32.240
[Amit Varma]: Prime Minister at that time and was able to shape early India, as opposed to pretty much

00:22:32.240 --> 00:22:36.680
[Amit Varma]: all the other leaders around him were of a different persuasion? And I don't mean that

00:22:36.680 --> 00:22:42.280
[Amit Varma]: necessarily in a negative way, but, you know, more of that. And secondly, could it also

00:22:42.280 --> 00:22:46.160
[Amit Varma]: be argued, and I have asked this question to various guests on my show and got very

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:52.480
[Amit Varma]: interesting answers, which is basically that our constitution, which to my mind is not

00:22:52.480 --> 00:22:58.200
[Amit Varma]: liberal enough, but is way more liberal than our society. Is our constitution, a liberal

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:05.440
[Amit Varma]: constitution imposed on an illiberal society? And if so, A, how can that imposition be liberal?

00:23:05.440 --> 00:23:12.320
[Amit Varma]: And B, then are the people who have taken, who have finally won the political battle today,

00:23:12.320 --> 00:23:15.920
[Amit Varma]: are they then justified in saying that this constitution has no validity?

00:23:15.920 --> 00:23:21.000
[Guest]: Right, you've packed quite a bit into that. So let me answer that. So the first question

00:23:21.000 --> 00:23:27.080
[Guest]: is about Nehru. So I often look back on Nehru, and I think we got very lucky with Nehru,

00:23:27.080 --> 00:23:33.280
[Guest]: because Nehru was one of his personality flaws was that he could look at society with an

00:23:33.280 --> 00:23:40.800
[Guest]: open mind, but he had his own prejudices. He looked at economics as the principal unit

00:23:40.800 --> 00:23:46.720
[Guest]: of organization. He couldn't appreciate until very later in life the role of religion in

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:56.200
[Guest]: shaping society. And so he, people who were passionate about religion, who wanted to organize

00:23:56.200 --> 00:24:02.960
[Guest]: around religion, he had great contempt for those people. And that's one of the reasons

00:24:02.960 --> 00:24:08.080
[Guest]: he didn't appreciate the popularity of the Muslim League until it was very late. But

00:24:08.080 --> 00:24:14.200
[Guest]: once Pakistan was founded, he was uncompromising in his resolve that India was not going to

00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:21.520
[Guest]: go down that path. And he was a man not only of moral rectitude, but also incredible physical

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:28.440
[Guest]: courage. I relate an incident in my book when, you know, he just get in a car and drive around

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:33.640
[Guest]: places in Delhi, where there was communal rioting, and he'd get personally involved

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:39.040
[Guest]: and try to stop violence. And in one instance, you know, he learned that a group of Sikhs

00:24:39.040 --> 00:24:44.000
[Guest]: was planning an attack against Muslims. And he told them, if you hurt a single hair on

00:24:44.000 --> 00:24:48.080
[Guest]: the head of a single Muslim, I'll send in tanks and blow you to bits. That was the kind

00:24:48.080 --> 00:24:53.320
[Guest]: of man he was. And then a Muslim shop owner rang him from Chandni Chowk. And he got through

00:24:53.320 --> 00:24:56.800
[Guest]: to Nehru, he rang the Prime Minister's office and Nehru answered the phone. You could do

00:24:56.800 --> 00:25:05.280
[Guest]: such things back in the day. And Nehru immediately got in the car and arrived on the scene and

00:25:05.280 --> 00:25:10.040
[Guest]: supervised clearance of the mobs. This was the kind of man Nehru was.

00:25:10.040 --> 00:25:14.800
[Guest]: Contrast this with Ehsan Jafri trying to get through to Modi when the attacks were happening.

00:25:14.800 --> 00:25:20.840
[Guest]: I've often contrasted that with Jinnah not paying a visit to refugee camps. But look

00:25:20.840 --> 00:25:25.800
[Guest]: at our own history. Let's leave Pakistan aside. LK Advani tried to get through to Modi and

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:31.440
[Guest]: LK Advani pleaded with Modi to send forces to Ehsan Jafri's house and Modi completely

00:25:31.440 --> 00:25:36.800
[Guest]: neglected that. That is the story, reportedly, I must add. And Ehsan Jafri was gashed to

00:25:36.800 --> 00:25:43.080
[Guest]: death by these people. So we got very, very lucky with Nehru, I think. Your second part

00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:45.240
[Guest]: of the question, sorry, you'll have to forgive me.

00:25:45.240 --> 00:25:51.600
[Amit Varma]: My second part of the question, therefore, was about what today's cultural warriors quote

00:25:51.600 --> 00:25:56.200
[Amit Varma]: unquote often talk about a liberal elite, which is out of touch with the nation.

00:25:56.200 --> 00:26:01.720
[Guest]: So the Constitution of India was not an imposition. There's a very fascinating book that I've

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:08.520
[Guest]: just finished reading by Madhav Khosla, India's founding movement. And he makes the argument

00:26:08.520 --> 00:26:14.280
[Guest]: that the Indian Constitution, Nehru was asked once, what do you think your legacy will be?

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:19.400
[Guest]: He said, probably, I hope 300 million Indians capable of governing themselves. What he meant

00:26:19.400 --> 00:26:25.640
[Guest]: by that was that the Indian democratic experiment was not so much an imposition as a training

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:29.800
[Guest]: exercise. It was creating citizens. It was making citizens of the people who had known

00:26:29.800 --> 00:26:34.720
[Guest]: only subjecthood. The Indian Constitution granted rights to people, even if they did

00:26:34.720 --> 00:26:39.040
[Guest]: not know how to exercise them. There were many arguments that said that the introduction

00:26:39.040 --> 00:26:43.160
[Guest]: of franchise suffrage should be phased, should be incremental. Those were rejected out of

00:26:43.160 --> 00:26:48.600
[Guest]: hand by people like Ambedkar, who said that the very act of giving them rights and inviting

00:26:48.600 --> 00:26:54.760
[Guest]: them to exercise those rights would be a form of cultivating democratic citizenship. And

00:26:54.760 --> 00:27:00.760
[Guest]: that's what has happened over the past seven decades. The breakthrough of Hindu nationalism

00:27:00.760 --> 00:27:06.520
[Guest]: has happened precisely because India is a democratic society. Had India been anti-democratic

00:27:06.520 --> 00:27:11.360
[Guest]: secular republic like Turkey, they would have been firing squads long time ago. And Hindu

00:27:11.360 --> 00:27:15.600
[Guest]: nationalists would not have been in a position to seize power. They have in Turkey. They

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:19.400
[Guest]: might have here, but not in the manner they have. They wouldn't have had the democratic

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:25.280
[Guest]: legitimacy they have today. So the Indian Constitution is not an imposition. It's not

00:27:25.280 --> 00:27:32.440
[Guest]: the vision that animates it is certainly liberal and the society to which that vision was being

00:27:32.440 --> 00:27:38.480
[Guest]: imparted was illiberal. But that is not to say that the Constitution itself was an imposition.

00:27:38.480 --> 00:27:44.200
[Guest]: The mismatch between the two only means that it bespeaks the audacity of the creators of

00:27:44.200 --> 00:27:49.280
[Guest]: the Constitution. It doesn't mean that India was ill suited for that Constitution. If anything,

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:55.720
[Guest]: Indian democracy has demonstrated the suitability of Indians. Indians are an extremely democratic

00:27:55.720 --> 00:27:56.720
[Amit Varma]: people.

00:27:56.720 --> 00:28:02.080
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, I have to point out here that I, I'm not against that particular imposition

00:28:02.080 --> 00:28:06.920
[Amit Varma]: in this case, but I will still hold that it's an imposition because while I agree about

00:28:06.920 --> 00:28:11.540
[Amit Varma]: the nobility of intent and also the pedagogical nature of the Constitution, which Madhav writes

00:28:11.540 --> 00:28:18.600
[Amit Varma]: about so well, in his book that it was not it was one of his tasks was to be an instruction

00:28:18.600 --> 00:28:24.920
[Amit Varma]: manual on how citizens could relate to each other as equals. And in that sense, it's very

00:28:24.920 --> 00:28:30.880
[Amit Varma]: underappreciated if anything, but regardless of that, the argument could be made that society

00:28:30.880 --> 00:28:36.620
[Amit Varma]: wasn't quite like that wasn't remotely as liberal and the argument and that then brings

00:28:36.620 --> 00:28:44.560
[Amit Varma]: up the paradox that the liberal constitution in its liberality, enabled the illiberal society

00:28:44.560 --> 00:28:49.120
[Amit Varma]: to sort of rise up against it and take over the politics of the day. Does that make any

00:28:49.120 --> 00:28:50.120
[Guest]: kind of sense to you?

00:28:50.120 --> 00:28:53.720
[Guest]: Yeah, it makes perfect sense. Because the rise of the liberal is only made possible

00:28:53.720 --> 00:29:00.760
[Guest]: by a liberal constitution. It is because the Constitution guaranteed qualified free speech.

00:29:00.760 --> 00:29:08.440
[Guest]: It is because the Constitution allowed the BJP to form to come into existence, that the

00:29:08.440 --> 00:29:13.920
[Guest]: BJP was able to succeed the Johnson. And it was able to mobilize people around the Ram

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:19.160
[Guest]: Janmabhoomi issue. It is precisely because of a liberal constitution that illiberal elements

00:29:19.160 --> 00:29:26.720
[Guest]: came, came to power. It is, and it is, that is not an argument to put an end to the liberal

00:29:26.720 --> 00:29:31.520
[Guest]: constitution. It is an argument to reclaim the liberal constitution.

00:29:31.520 --> 00:29:36.080
[Amit Varma]: I think I know, I agree with you, but I'd phrase it differently. What I would say is

00:29:36.080 --> 00:29:42.180
[Amit Varma]: it is not an argument to end the liberal constitution. It is an argument to spread liberal values

00:29:42.180 --> 00:29:48.300
[Amit Varma]: in society. So they arise from the culture in a bottom up way, instead of from the polity

00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:53.520
[Amit Varma]: in a top down way. Because anything which comes from the polity in a top down way will

00:29:53.520 --> 00:29:57.840
[Amit Varma]: inevitably break unless the culture also shares the same values.

00:29:57.840 --> 00:30:07.640
[Guest]: I could not agree with you more in that sense, because unless people are educated to understand

00:30:07.640 --> 00:30:12.960
[Guest]: what they're being given, they will misuse it. It is, to use an extremely crude example,

00:30:12.960 --> 00:30:18.160
[Guest]: if you install a Western toilet in a place where people aren't accustomed to using those,

00:30:18.160 --> 00:30:22.960
[Guest]: they will not be able to use it properly. And it will become rather obsolete very quickly.

00:30:22.960 --> 00:30:29.480
[Guest]: But I don't think that is the case with India, because the Indian constitution and the values

00:30:29.480 --> 00:30:37.320
[Guest]: that drive that constitution and the Republic of India is not ill suited to Indian needs.

00:30:37.320 --> 00:30:44.000
[Guest]: I think it does meet the Indian need. And what was the principal Indian need? The principal

00:30:44.000 --> 00:30:52.680
[Guest]: Indian need was to undo the injustice of caste, was to emancipate the individual from the

00:30:52.680 --> 00:30:59.840
[Guest]: grip of the community. You could not, I think, do those things without creating a charter

00:30:59.840 --> 00:31:05.920
[Guest]: of rights, without creating a state that would forcefully enforce those rights. And that

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:13.040
[Guest]: is what the Indian constitution did. Where it failed, I think, is not in its conception,

00:31:13.040 --> 00:31:19.400
[Guest]: but it's in its execution. If anything, I think the Indian state wasn't forceful enough.

00:31:19.400 --> 00:31:23.880
[Guest]: And that's where I think your argument that the society itself, that people, the institutions

00:31:23.880 --> 00:31:27.960
[Guest]: created by the state fail to enforce those rights and ideas.

00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:31.600
[Amit Varma]: So, to come back to what you're saying that I'll again disagree. And you know, you said

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:37.400
[Amit Varma]: that the conception was correct, the execution was flawed. I would say that the execution

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:43.120
[Amit Varma]: being flawed is a result of the conception being flawed. Because number one, I would

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:48.200
[Amit Varma]: say that this coercive power of the state is not going to solve any of these problems.

00:31:48.200 --> 00:31:51.840
[Amit Varma]: In fact, none of these problems have been solved. We are still, you know, the caste

00:31:51.840 --> 00:31:58.600
[Amit Varma]: problem is still acute. Women are still second class citizens. Economically, we are still

00:31:58.600 --> 00:32:03.960
[Amit Varma]: desperately poor, though much better off because of various events of happenstance, but nowhere

00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:08.200
[Amit Varma]: near where we should have been. And I would say a lot of this is because of the coercive

00:32:08.200 --> 00:32:12.920
[Amit Varma]: power of the state gone wrong. And another argument I have made, and this was a question

00:32:12.920 --> 00:32:18.160
[Amit Varma]: I wanted to ask you numerous times while reading your book, is one of the things that you're

00:32:18.160 --> 00:32:23.360
[Amit Varma]: book does very well, and we'll go over some of that is point out who pretty much all the

00:32:23.360 --> 00:32:28.620
[Amit Varma]: people who led our country were desperately flawed, perhaps Nehru the least, but even

00:32:28.620 --> 00:32:34.760
[Amit Varma]: he was desperately flawed. And I have made the case before that, for that you need to

00:32:34.760 --> 00:32:39.560
[Amit Varma]: look at incentives, the incentives that bring politicians into politics, which again has

00:32:39.560 --> 00:32:44.840
[Amit Varma]: to do with the conception of the kind of state we should be in the sense that the reason

00:32:44.840 --> 00:32:49.360
[Amit Varma]: our freedom fighters were such great leaders by so many great leaders emerged during that

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:53.920
[Amit Varma]: time is that they weren't incentivized by a lust for power, because there was no power

00:32:53.920 --> 00:32:58.240
[Amit Varma]: to be had. They were fighting for certain abstract ideals, they believed in them enough

00:32:58.240 --> 00:33:03.480
[Amit Varma]: to die for them. And therefore, you had that great generation of leaders, you do not have

00:33:03.480 --> 00:33:08.740
[Amit Varma]: leaders like that today, not because people in general are bad, or the bad people happen

00:33:08.740 --> 00:33:13.240
[Amit Varma]: to get to the top, but simply because the incentives of politics are different. The

00:33:13.240 --> 00:33:19.680
[Amit Varma]: state is so powerful. And the course of hand of the state is so appealing, that you have

00:33:19.680 --> 00:33:23.520
[Amit Varma]: this interplay between money and power, which is inevitable in a democracy, if you don't

00:33:23.520 --> 00:33:27.200
[Amit Varma]: watch out for it, where to win elections, you need a lot of money, and then money needs

00:33:27.200 --> 00:33:31.600
[Amit Varma]: return on interest. And the more coercive power the state has, the greater the return

00:33:31.600 --> 00:33:37.800
[Amit Varma]: on interest. And therefore, you end up with these sort of sociopathic semi mafia goon

00:33:37.800 --> 00:33:43.480
[Amit Varma]: type of leaders, where I argued at all political parties, actually, different mafia gangs are

00:33:43.480 --> 00:33:47.920
[Amit Varma]: competing to get the monopoly on violence for five years, or whatever the period might

00:33:47.920 --> 00:33:53.000
[Amit Varma]: be. So I'd say that at a fundamental level, we need to imagine, we need to re examine

00:33:53.000 --> 00:33:57.200
[Amit Varma]: the design itself, the conception itself, by which I don't mean that constitution per

00:33:57.200 --> 00:34:01.840
[Amit Varma]: se, because I'm sure most of the things you admire about it, are things I admire as well.

00:34:01.840 --> 00:34:06.960
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not complaining about its quote, unquote, imposition, I'm just saying that this will

00:34:06.960 --> 00:34:11.800
[Amit Varma]: only work this great Indian experiment can only work if it comes from the bottom up through

00:34:11.800 --> 00:34:16.000
[Amit Varma]: society through our culture. And we have utterly failed in that.

00:34:16.000 --> 00:34:22.800
[Guest]: So to answer that question, you have to look at the Congress Party. Now, the Congress Party

00:34:22.800 --> 00:34:29.880
[Guest]: is created to fight the British to fight British imperialism, which is a noble cause. And there

00:34:29.880 --> 00:34:34.320
[Guest]: are no incentives in fighting the British, you don't get bags of cash, you don't get

00:34:34.320 --> 00:34:38.520
[Guest]: high office. But nonetheless, you fight the British because it is an ideal you believe

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:45.160
[Guest]: in. And that drives people to join the Congress. That drives people to relinquish everything

00:34:45.160 --> 00:34:51.720
[Guest]: their relationships, their homes, their incomes, to fight for this cause. Congress becomes

00:34:51.720 --> 00:34:58.200
[Guest]: a vehicle for the realization of Indian independence. Once India becomes independent, what is the

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:05.080
[Guest]: Congress Party? What is its purpose? Mahatma Gandhi says, let's dissolve Congress, because

00:35:05.080 --> 00:35:09.960
[Guest]: it has served its purpose. Now India needs to look at itself differently. India needs

00:35:09.960 --> 00:35:15.000
[Guest]: different kinds of parties, India needs to govern itself differently. But Congress becomes

00:35:15.000 --> 00:35:22.640
[Guest]: a post independence, a political party for the Republic. This creates a problem, because

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:29.380
[Guest]: the Congress Party is a beneficiary of a great fund of goodwill, goodwill generated by its

00:35:29.380 --> 00:35:34.280
[Guest]: work during the freedom movement. So the result of this goodwill is that it is bound to win

00:35:34.280 --> 00:35:38.800
[Guest]: four or five elections, no matter what it does, it is guaranteed five electoral victories.

00:35:38.800 --> 00:35:44.360
[Guest]: And it wins those electoral victories. But in the course of winning those electoral victories,

00:35:44.360 --> 00:35:49.560
[Guest]: the ambitions of the people who sit at the top of the Congress Party alter. The first

00:35:49.560 --> 00:35:55.800
[Guest]: generation of Congress Party leaders are animated by the desire to create a great socialist

00:35:55.800 --> 00:36:01.600
[Guest]: republic. They are animated by Nehru's vision. But the second generation of leaders are animated

00:36:01.600 --> 00:36:05.680
[Guest]: by something different. They are animated by the desire to perpetuate themselves, to

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:12.520
[Guest]: leave their stamp on history, to remake India in their own mould, to build cults of personality.

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:19.200
[Guest]: And no one does this with more egregiousness than Indira Gandhi and her son Sanjay Gandhi.

00:36:19.200 --> 00:36:25.520
[Guest]: This is the point at which it is not India that becomes, it is not India that falls first.

00:36:25.520 --> 00:36:30.680
[Guest]: It is the Congress Party that falls first. And we have to remember that Congress Party

00:36:30.680 --> 00:36:36.440
[Guest]: for a very long time was India. It really spoke for India for a very long time. Its

00:36:36.440 --> 00:36:43.640
[Guest]: values were reflected in the constitution. Its values were the values of India. What

00:36:43.640 --> 00:36:50.240
[Guest]: the Congress felt was India was what the world thought India was for a very long time. Congress

00:36:50.240 --> 00:36:55.320
[Guest]: was socialist, so India was socialist. Congress was secular, so India was secular. Congress

00:36:55.320 --> 00:37:00.880
[Guest]: believed in non-interventionism and non-alignment, so India was non-interventionist and non-aligned.

00:37:00.880 --> 00:37:07.760
[Guest]: And Congress was democratic, India was democratic. And what did Mrs. Gandhi attack first? She

00:37:07.760 --> 00:37:13.280
[Guest]: attacked the democratic pillar of the Congress Party. She destroyed that. And she created

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:21.240
[Guest]: a cult of personality around herself. Once the Congress Party fell to the Gandhi family,

00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:28.120
[Guest]: India fell to the Gandhi family. And the gangsterization of Indian politics began under Sanjay Gandhi.

00:37:28.120 --> 00:37:33.640
[Guest]: The caliber of people, initially, Mrs. Gandhi's advisors were a group of very scrupulous Kashmiri

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:41.320
[Guest]: pundits. Subsequently, Sanjay Gandhi infested the Congress Party with thugs from Punjab

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:45.560
[Guest]: and other places. So, the caliber of these people, they were men like Bansi Lal.

00:37:45.560 --> 00:37:51.080
[Amit Varma]: The repulsive remnants of that gang of people include Kamal Nath, our current Chief Minister.

00:37:51.080 --> 00:37:55.120
[Guest]: Kamal Nath, Pranab Mukherjee, in fact, was brought in by Sanjay Gandhi. There are other

00:37:55.120 --> 00:38:00.440
[Guest]: names that miss me. Ambika Soni was one of the people who came in via the Sanjay gate.

00:38:00.440 --> 00:38:06.200
[Guest]: This is the moment at which Congress becomes something else entirely. It loses its moral

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:14.240
[Guest]: luster. It becomes a vehicle for the perpetuation of one family's power. Congress was a dynastic

00:38:14.240 --> 00:38:19.280
[Guest]: force before. Motilal Nehru was a Congress President. He orchestrated Nehru's rise within

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:23.840
[Guest]: the party. Nehru, you know, looked the other way when Indira Gandhi was rising. But those

00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:29.840
[Guest]: were faults of omission. Those were fairly benign actions. In retrospect, they look more

00:38:29.840 --> 00:38:35.880
[Guest]: egregious than they actually were at the time. But what Indira Gandhi does is consciously

00:38:35.880 --> 00:38:42.320
[Guest]: egregious because she decides to install her son as the leader of the Congress Party. And

00:38:42.320 --> 00:38:48.120
[Guest]: Congress never really recovers from the 70s. And India never really recovers from that

00:38:48.120 --> 00:38:56.920
[Guest]: moment. But the reaction to the Congress Party, once Congress has lost its moral luster, the

00:38:56.920 --> 00:39:02.480
[Guest]: Hindu nationalists, the opponents of the Congress Party, the communists, the rest, are now more

00:39:02.480 --> 00:39:07.720
[Guest]: freely able to say that this is not the party that won us the Indian independence. This

00:39:07.720 --> 00:39:14.160
[Guest]: is the plaything of one family. And they gain greater legitimacy in the eyes of people.

00:39:14.160 --> 00:39:21.920
[Guest]: And the collapse of democracy within the Congress Party is actually the beginning of democratic

00:39:21.920 --> 00:39:27.200
[Guest]: expansion within India because the alternatives to the Congress Party have a more legitimate

00:39:27.200 --> 00:39:33.440
[Guest]: claim to make against the Congress Party. And you see, it is from the 70s, it is in

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:37.960
[Guest]: the 70s that for the first time Congress Party is defeated. Mrs. Gandhi loses her seat. Sanjay

00:39:37.960 --> 00:39:43.960
[Guest]: Gandhi loses his deposit. So, you talked about the liberal leading to the liberal. This is

00:39:43.960 --> 00:39:47.800
[Guest]: actually an illustration of that. You know, many of the people who fought against Mrs.

00:39:47.800 --> 00:39:53.660
[Guest]: Gandhi were ideologically not very liberal. But they were Democrats. You know, they vehemently

00:39:53.660 --> 00:39:58.440
[Guest]: opposed what she did to the constitution. And many of the people whom we would associate

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:03.120
[Guest]: with Hindu nationalism were actually people who were willing to respect the constitution,

00:40:03.120 --> 00:40:09.320
[Guest]: willing to function as Democrats. And what happened to the Congress Party was profoundly

00:40:09.320 --> 00:40:15.880
[Guest]: shocking for them. And they lost their faith. This was a moment when a lot of people who

00:40:15.880 --> 00:40:22.040
[Guest]: believed in India were disillusioned. But they also fought very hard to reclaim India.

00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:28.840
[Guest]: And alas, the mystique of dynasty, the incompetence of the government that replaced Mrs. Gandhi

00:40:28.840 --> 00:40:32.660
[Guest]: meant that Mrs. Gandhi was voted back into power again. But the Congress Party had by

00:40:32.660 --> 00:40:38.920
[Guest]: then ceased to be a democratic force at all. The Congress Party was nothing but the property

00:40:38.920 --> 00:40:45.400
[Guest]: of the Gandhi family. And once Mrs. Gandhi died, Rajiv Gandhi was installed in office.

00:40:45.400 --> 00:40:53.520
[Guest]: And here you see the complete poverty, ideological poverty of Rajiv Gandhi. He had no convictions

00:40:53.520 --> 00:41:01.580
[Guest]: at all. And he presided over the total dissolution of the secular state bequeathed by his grandfather.

00:41:01.580 --> 00:41:08.000
[Guest]: He made a series of concessions to competing communists. He banned the satanic verses.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:14.760
[Guest]: He imposed a roundabout ban on it, not a direct ban. He opened Ayodhya, the Babri Masjid.

00:41:14.760 --> 00:41:19.960
[Guest]: He legislated to deny Shah Bano alimony granted to her by the Supreme Court of India, driving

00:41:19.960 --> 00:41:25.720
[Guest]: Arif Mohammad Khan, who was a liberal congressman, out of the party. And he claimed to be Mr.

00:41:25.720 --> 00:41:32.640
[Guest]: Clean, became involved in one of the worst corruption scandals of the time. And he claimed

00:41:32.640 --> 00:41:40.120
[Guest]: to be an inheritor of the mantle of non-alignment and yet made India militarily a party to the

00:41:40.120 --> 00:41:46.720
[Guest]: conflict, civil war in Sri Lanka, and paid the price for it, sadly, with his life. But

00:41:46.720 --> 00:41:54.360
[Guest]: this is a point at which the legitimacy of the Congress Party is in tatters. And alternative

00:41:54.360 --> 00:42:03.400
[Guest]: arguments have a wide audience. If the Congress Party had remained morally untainted, I don't

00:42:03.400 --> 00:42:11.120
[Guest]: think the BJP could have made such a forceful breakthrough as it did in the 80s and 90s,

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:18.760
[Guest]: such an impressive breakthrough. Every time we think about the detrition of Indian institutions

00:42:18.760 --> 00:42:26.320
[Guest]: and what India has become subsequently, the decay of India's values, we must look at Congress,

00:42:26.320 --> 00:42:30.600
[Guest]: because the history of the Congress Party is really the history of India, politically

00:42:30.600 --> 00:42:37.440
[Amit Varma]: speaking, looking at the state. That's a beautiful illustration of, you know, a degradation over

00:42:37.440 --> 00:42:41.800
[Amit Varma]: time because of what I would say is incentives. Before I sort of elaborate on one aspect of

00:42:41.800 --> 00:42:45.720
[Amit Varma]: that which came to mind as you were speaking, I'd also like to, you know, you have a really

00:42:45.720 --> 00:42:50.720
[Amit Varma]: nice anecdote in your book about how, you know, Rajiv Gandhi looked upon as such a clean

00:42:50.720 --> 00:42:54.880
[Amit Varma]: character, good person, well meaning, so and so. And you have an anecdote about, I'll quote

00:42:54.880 --> 00:43:00.280
[Amit Varma]: from your book, quote, who could forget his visit to Andhra Pradesh in 1982, soon after

00:43:00.280 --> 00:43:04.680
[Amit Varma]: being installed by his mother as a party's general secretary. The chief minister of the

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:10.240
[Amit Varma]: state, Tanguturi Anjaya, a Dalit, went to receive him at the airport. In this, he was

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:15.360
[Amit Varma]: following the custom instituted by Sanjay. But Rajiv, who considered himself modern,

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:20.400
[Amit Varma]: took great umbrage and exploded with invective. The chief minister had endured a lifetime

00:43:20.400 --> 00:43:25.040
[Amit Varma]: of vicious abuse at the hands of upper caste Hindus, many of whom still considered physical

00:43:25.040 --> 00:43:30.240
[Amit Varma]: contact with him spiritually defiling, but being berated in late life by a man half his

00:43:30.240 --> 00:43:36.040
[Amit Varma]: age broke him. He began to shed tears. Rajiv called him a buffoon and drove away, stop

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:40.040
[Amit Varma]: quote. And a couple of thoughts. One is, of course, an observation that a friend had once

00:43:40.040 --> 00:43:44.680
[Amit Varma]: made that if you look at the Nehru Gandhi family, what you see is that with each generation,

00:43:44.680 --> 00:43:48.200
[Amit Varma]: they get more and more incompetent, which seems to me broadly to be correct, and which

00:43:48.200 --> 00:43:54.920
[Amit Varma]: also seems to align with another observation, which is perhaps pure happenstance that with

00:43:54.920 --> 00:44:00.440
[Amit Varma]: each generation of leaders within the Hindutva movement, they tend to get more and more radical

00:44:00.440 --> 00:44:05.840
[Amit Varma]: all the way from, you know, Vajpayee to Advani to Modi to Shah to perhaps Adityanath next

00:44:05.840 --> 00:44:11.440
[Amit Varma]: and God knows what. But the larger point that your story kind of brought up is that when

00:44:11.440 --> 00:44:17.120
[Amit Varma]: I was earlier speaking of incentives mattering, it was not just in the kind of people who

00:44:17.120 --> 00:44:21.540
[Amit Varma]: join politics, you know, good people joining for the right reasons, bad people joining

00:44:21.540 --> 00:44:27.600
[Amit Varma]: for the wrong reasons, but also that within the same individual, you see different responses

00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:34.840
[Amit Varma]: to incentives. And this is really illustrated in your book by, you know, the sort of change

00:44:34.840 --> 00:44:38.480
[Amit Varma]: that happened within Nehru itself. I mean, there were early signs of it, like you point

00:44:38.480 --> 00:44:43.080
[Amit Varma]: out in 1929, at the Congress Party Convention in Lahore, Jawaharlal rode a white horse to

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:47.880
[Amit Varma]: the convention, and the crowd screamed long live Jawaharlal Nehru, the uncrowned King

00:44:47.880 --> 00:44:53.200
[Amit Varma]: of India, one of the anecdotes in your book. But what is also a fascinating paragraph for

00:44:53.200 --> 00:44:58.600
[Amit Varma]: me, and again, I'd like to sort of read it out. And here you talk about Nehru post independence,

00:44:58.600 --> 00:45:03.720
[Amit Varma]: and you say, quote, the man who in the colonial period had observed that logic can always

00:45:03.720 --> 00:45:09.480
[Amit Varma]: be made to fit in with the desires and irrepressible urges of a person was in the republican era,

00:45:09.480 --> 00:45:14.720
[Amit Varma]: capable of rationalizing frequent departures from his avowed beliefs, the principled anti

00:45:14.720 --> 00:45:19.680
[Amit Varma]: imperialist and acolyte of Mahatma Gandhi, who never tired of dispensing prelections

00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:25.400
[Amit Varma]: about peace to modern leaders had few misgivings about utilizing disproportionate force against

00:45:25.400 --> 00:45:29.800
[Amit Varma]: people he claimed as his own. In Kerala in the south, he engineered the overthrow of

00:45:29.800 --> 00:45:34.760
[Amit Varma]: a democratically elected communist government. In Kashmir in the north, he presided over

00:45:34.760 --> 00:45:39.920
[Amit Varma]: an anti democratic farce. In Nagaland to the east, he authorized the bombing of Christians

00:45:39.920 --> 00:45:44.920
[Amit Varma]: who had had the temerity to demand from India, what India had sought from the British, the

00:45:44.920 --> 00:45:50.420
[Amit Varma]: Armed Forces Special Powers Act, an extraordinarily repressive piece of legislation enacted by

00:45:50.420 --> 00:45:56.240
[Amit Varma]: Parliament in 1958, to grant impunity to agents of the state dispatched to stamp out insurgencies

00:45:56.240 --> 00:46:03.080
[Amit Varma]: in India's peripheries, embodied Nehru's ruthless resolve to preserve the Indian Union at any

00:46:03.080 --> 00:46:08.800
[Amit Varma]: expense, a stop code. And at one hand, all of this is obviously, you know, Nehru very

00:46:08.800 --> 00:46:13.720
[Amit Varma]: oddly and something that as a student of Gandhi, he would never have done stops disregarding

00:46:13.720 --> 00:46:20.800
[Amit Varma]: means as an end in itself. And secondly, you see this corrosiveness in his character where

00:46:20.800 --> 00:46:25.520
[Amit Varma]: he is doing all of these things, perhaps with some self awareness, perhaps with one none

00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:30.360
[Amit Varma]: one doesn't know, and and also enabling dynasty, you know, in Indira became president of the

00:46:30.360 --> 00:46:34.680
[Amit Varma]: Congress Party in his lifetime. And as you point out in the book, his cabinet colleagues

00:46:34.680 --> 00:46:39.960
[Amit Varma]: felt that he was grooming her for dynasty. Is this a story that to you as a student of

00:46:39.960 --> 00:46:44.400
[Amit Varma]: history as well seems poignant that men have so many different shades to them, and how

00:46:44.400 --> 00:46:46.360
[Amit Varma]: you can fall with circumstances?

00:46:46.360 --> 00:46:51.040
[Guest]: Yeah, in the case of Nehru, once he became the Prime Minister of India, his greatest

00:46:51.040 --> 00:46:55.660
[Guest]: obsession was holding this thing together. I also mentioned you've obviously elaborately

00:46:55.660 --> 00:47:01.260
[Guest]: quoted from the book, but I also mentioned in the book that Nehru was a democrat at heart.

00:47:01.260 --> 00:47:05.920
[Guest]: He often didn't get his way. And he accepted that when he didn't get his way. He wasn't

00:47:05.920 --> 00:47:11.000
[Guest]: an authoritarian. You could make the argument that he wasn't an authoritarian because he

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:14.940
[Guest]: didn't have the need to become an authoritarian. The Congress Party really listened to everything

00:47:14.940 --> 00:47:19.880
[Guest]: he said. He was held in tremendous esteem by the public, and he got his way for them

00:47:19.880 --> 00:47:25.680
[Guest]: for almost anything he wanted. For most of his life, he got his way most of his prime

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:31.440
[Guest]: ministerial career. So he didn't really have the need to be an authoritarian. And yet,

00:47:31.440 --> 00:47:37.640
[Guest]: to people in Kerala, to people in Kashmir, to people in the East, he was an authoritarian.

00:47:37.640 --> 00:47:43.720
[Guest]: His conduct was a departure, a shocking departure from everything he claimed to believe in.

00:47:43.720 --> 00:47:49.840
[Guest]: That part of Nehru must not be effaced or airbrushed, because we need to appreciate

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:58.720
[Guest]: Nehru fully as a whole. And part of the reason Nehru did this is because he became very insecure

00:47:58.720 --> 00:48:07.320
[Guest]: about Indian unity. This is the irony. Once you give people the rights, they demand things.

00:48:07.320 --> 00:48:13.440
[Guest]: And once they demand things, the state finds it very difficult to grant them those things.

00:48:13.440 --> 00:48:20.060
[Guest]: And this conflict was illustrated by Nehru's conduct in different parts of the country.

00:48:20.060 --> 00:48:25.800
[Guest]: This does not take away from the fact that Nehru was an extraordinary figure, and this

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:30.720
[Guest]: does not take away from the fact that India was lucky to have Nehru in so many ways. But

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:37.520
[Guest]: it nonetheless remains a fact that Nehru did institute certain practices. He did give us

00:48:37.520 --> 00:48:42.640
[Guest]: the AFSPA, which we still haven't been able to relinquish after all these years. It is

00:48:42.640 --> 00:48:49.080
[Guest]: still used against our own citizens. And we still live with his legacy in Kashmir. And

00:48:49.080 --> 00:48:54.360
[Guest]: his most damaging legacy, of course, I'm sorry to say, is his family. We still live with

00:48:54.360 --> 00:48:59.960
[Guest]: that. And we haven't recovered from what the family has done to this country over the years.

00:48:59.960 --> 00:49:04.560
[Amit Varma]: I'd say in a sense, they are the sort of symptom and not the disease. In the sense, again,

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:10.680
[Amit Varma]: I think a problem goes back to the conception of the state itself. You know, before we head

00:49:10.680 --> 00:49:15.560
[Amit Varma]: over to Greg, I want to quickly take a poetic break, which is, you know, towards the end

00:49:15.560 --> 00:49:21.000
[Amit Varma]: of your book, you've quoted Sahir Ludhianvi, which is very interesting because Sahir Ludhianvi

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:27.600
[Amit Varma]: was one of those Muslims who came from Pakistan to India. And he wrote sort of these beautiful

00:49:27.600 --> 00:49:28.600
[Amit Varma]: lines.

00:49:28.600 --> 00:49:34.520
[Amit Varma]: Wo waqt gaya, wo daur gaya, jab do kaumon ka nara tha. Wo log gaye is dharti se, jinka

00:49:34.520 --> 00:49:42.080
[Amit Varma]: maqsat batwara tha, ab ek hai sab hindustani. And broadly, I'll make an attempt to translate

00:49:42.080 --> 00:49:47.680
[Amit Varma]: it. That time is gone, that age is gone. When slogans spoke of two nations, those people

00:49:47.680 --> 00:49:53.400
[Amit Varma]: too have left this land who aim for our separations. Now all Indians are one. Now all Indians are

00:49:53.400 --> 00:49:57.320
[Amit Varma]: one. And I want to ask you more about this after we come back for a quick commercial

00:49:57.320 --> 00:50:00.560
[Amit Varma]: break.

