[Amit Varma]: fabulous book Malevolent Republic. You know, and before we went into the break, I quoted

00:51:20.160 --> 00:51:26.160
[Amit Varma]: Saeed Ludhianvi's beautiful poem, which you quoted in your book as well. And my next question

00:51:26.160 --> 00:51:31.320
[Amit Varma]: is sort of touches on that theme because it struck me and this is something you say elsewhere

00:51:31.320 --> 00:51:36.200
[Amit Varma]: in the book also when you're talking about Hyderabad. It struck me that Saeed Ludhianvi

00:51:36.200 --> 00:51:42.240
[Amit Varma]: was a Muslim who came from Pakistan to India. It strikes me that those Muslims who chose

00:51:42.240 --> 00:51:49.280
[Amit Varma]: to stay back in India actually made a greater act of faith in what we understand as our

00:51:49.280 --> 00:51:53.240
[Amit Varma]: idea of India than even the Hindus did. The Hindus kind of just stayed back by default,

00:51:53.240 --> 00:51:56.440
[Amit Varma]: right? They are where they are, but they were Muslims who could go to Pakistan and choose

00:51:56.440 --> 00:52:00.160
[Amit Varma]: that view of the world and who could stay here and could choose the secular view of

00:52:00.160 --> 00:52:04.600
[Amit Varma]: the world. And they chose to stay back and in a sense are more committed to the idea

00:52:04.600 --> 00:52:08.680
[Amit Varma]: of India as it were. I'm reminded of that old joke about how do you define the difference

00:52:08.680 --> 00:52:13.880
[Amit Varma]: between interested and committed? And you know, you take an egg and you take sausage.

00:52:13.880 --> 00:52:18.080
[Amit Varma]: And in the case of the egg, the chicken is interested. But in the case of the sausage,

00:52:18.080 --> 00:52:23.560
[Amit Varma]: the pig is committed. And it seems to me like that the Indian Muslim by staying here committed

00:52:23.560 --> 00:52:29.000
[Guest]: himself to the idea of India. I think many of us forget what it must have been like for

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:35.200
[Guest]: Muslims at partition. You know, all your core religious are fleeing to Pakistan. There is

00:52:35.200 --> 00:52:40.560
[Guest]: violence on the streets. There are refugees from Pakistan who want to hunt you down. Your

00:52:40.560 --> 00:52:46.700
[Guest]: businesses are being burnt down to the ground. And still you choose to remain. You choose

00:52:46.700 --> 00:52:52.120
[Guest]: to reject the blandishments of paradise in Pakistan. You refuse to vacate India. And

00:52:52.120 --> 00:52:57.440
[Guest]: you say this is my home. And you say this is your home not only because of the surroundings.

00:52:57.440 --> 00:53:01.440
[Guest]: Obviously there is that. This is where you grew up. This is your natural habitat. But

00:53:01.440 --> 00:53:06.640
[Guest]: the habitat is ceasing to exist. But you choose to exist. You choose to remain in India because

00:53:06.640 --> 00:53:11.560
[Guest]: of the compact that India is making with you, making with all its citizens. If you're a

00:53:11.560 --> 00:53:14.880
[Guest]: Hindu, you don't really have to make that choice. But if you're a Muslim, you have an

00:53:14.880 --> 00:53:18.000
[Guest]: option. You have a choice. You have a menu in front of you. Do you remain in India or

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:26.240
[Guest]: do you go to Pakistan? And to choose India is an act of faith, as you say. And it is

00:53:26.240 --> 00:53:35.380
[Guest]: an act of commitment to the idea of an inclusive, secular India and a repudiation of an exclusionary

00:53:35.380 --> 00:53:43.760
[Guest]: Islamic Pakistan. That is one of the reasons I think India has a special responsibility

00:53:43.760 --> 00:53:50.520
[Guest]: to its Muslim citizens because they chose to be here. They made a choice by risking

00:53:50.520 --> 00:53:55.180
[Guest]: everything. They put their lives on the line. When Sahir moved to India, Muslims were still

00:53:55.180 --> 00:54:01.800
[Guest]: leaving for Pakistan. And Sahir made a political and a personal choice. He said, I belong to

00:54:01.800 --> 00:54:07.560
[Guest]: the multiplicity that is India. I'm part of that multitude. I'm a drop in that multitude

00:54:07.560 --> 00:54:13.920
[Guest]: of drops known as India. And he made the contrary wise journey and he came to India. Qurettulain

00:54:13.920 --> 00:54:18.600
[Guest]: Heather was another writer who came to India from Pakistan and she wrote this extraordinary

00:54:18.600 --> 00:54:23.880
[Guest]: novel called Rivers of Fire, in which she reclaimed 5000 years of Indian history. It

00:54:23.880 --> 00:54:31.960
[Guest]: starts 5000 years ago and it ends in contemporary India. It's a way of reclaiming your heritage.

00:54:31.960 --> 00:54:41.880
[Guest]: It's a way of submerging yourself in India. And the tragedy here is the Muslims who wanted

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:54.340
[Guest]: Pakistan have left. They're gone. They've gone. They've vacated this land. They no longer

00:54:54.340 --> 00:55:00.040
[Guest]: exist here. If you are angry and resentful about partition, the people to blame are the

00:55:00.040 --> 00:55:04.400
[Guest]: people who live in Pakistan, for whom partition hasn't ended. They still continue to make

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:09.240
[Guest]: savage demands on Indian territory. Be tough with them. Modi wasn't tough with them in

00:55:09.240 --> 00:55:12.920
[Guest]: his first term, if you remember. He went to Pakistan. He attended the wedding of a member

00:55:12.920 --> 00:55:18.080
[Guest]: of Nawaz Sharif's family. He was sending gifts to Nawaz Sharif's mother. Congress, successive

00:55:18.080 --> 00:55:22.560
[Guest]: Congress governments haven't been tough with Pakistan. They've instead unleashed themselves.

00:55:22.560 --> 00:55:27.760
[Guest]: They've unburdened their resentments on Indian Muslims who are not to be blamed for partition,

00:55:27.760 --> 00:55:31.040
[Guest]: who actually chose India. So that is the tragedy of this.

00:55:31.040 --> 00:55:38.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, they have deposed more faith in India than Hindu hardliners have, who hold the same

00:55:38.080 --> 00:55:42.880
[Amit Varma]: sort of two-nation theory that Jinnah had dear to themselves. And this also, what you're

00:55:42.880 --> 00:55:47.000
[Amit Varma]: saying, the choices of not just the extraordinary individuals you named, like Sai Ludhianvi

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:52.320
[Amit Varma]: and Kuratul and Haidar, but also millions of ordinary Muslims who made this choice.

00:55:52.320 --> 00:55:57.800
[Amit Varma]: What this also does is it gives a lie to the notion that I articulated before the break,

00:55:57.800 --> 00:56:02.680
[Amit Varma]: that you know, our constitution or our liberalism was something unnatural. It was imposed from

00:56:02.680 --> 00:56:08.560
[Amit Varma]: top and that the people culturally were always what you find a reflection of in today's politics.

00:56:08.560 --> 00:56:14.240
[Amit Varma]: But that's not the case because there is also a deep strand in our society, which is inclusive,

00:56:14.240 --> 00:56:19.240
[Amit Varma]: which is inclusionary and not exclusionary, which is assimilative in all the best ways,

00:56:19.240 --> 00:56:24.080
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, another reason I would say that the party in power today is not conservative,

00:56:24.080 --> 00:56:29.480
[Amit Varma]: but radical because they are trying to strike down these very deep strains in our Indian

00:56:29.480 --> 00:56:38.080
[Amit Varma]: culture. And this would also then seem to indicate that secularism is not just an abstract

00:56:38.080 --> 00:56:42.800
[Amit Varma]: Western concept, which has been imported by our leaders, but a lived Indian concept, even

00:56:42.800 --> 00:56:47.380
[Amit Varma]: though you may not have, you know, sort of use this term for it. What's your reaction

00:56:47.380 --> 00:56:52.800
[Amit Varma]: to this? And also, what's your take on the political conception of secularism and where

00:56:52.800 --> 00:56:53.800
[Guest]: it led us?

00:56:53.800 --> 00:56:59.640
[Guest]: So, what we think of as secularism is merely the codification of the lived reality of India.

00:56:59.640 --> 00:57:04.440
[Guest]: The fundamental truth of India is not intolerance, but tolerance. We have so many communities,

00:57:04.440 --> 00:57:08.640
[Guest]: we have so many linguistic minorities, we have so many religious ethnic minorities,

00:57:08.640 --> 00:57:13.360
[Guest]: we get along together for the most part. And that's because people live cheek by jowl with

00:57:13.360 --> 00:57:19.480
[Guest]: people who are unlike themselves. And they have over years figured out ways to coexist.

00:57:19.480 --> 00:57:24.760
[Guest]: And this Indian secularism, the state secularism, merely codified what is the lived reality

00:57:24.760 --> 00:57:33.640
[Guest]: of most Indians. What the BJP seeks to do is to transform us into a Hindu version of

00:57:33.640 --> 00:57:40.020
[Guest]: Pakistan, by which I mean that it seeks to redefine the individual by his or her faith.

00:57:40.020 --> 00:57:45.620
[Guest]: So if you are a Hindu, you are a natural citizen of this country. And if you are a non-Hindu,

00:57:45.620 --> 00:57:51.880
[Guest]: then you live here on the sufferings of Hindus. That is not how the Indian state was conceptualized.

00:57:51.880 --> 00:57:58.500
[Guest]: And the Indian state's conceptualization is the condition of Indian unity. Secularism

00:57:58.500 --> 00:58:07.380
[Guest]: is the basis upon which Indian unity was founded. Without you take away secularism, there is

00:58:07.380 --> 00:58:17.060
[Guest]: no means, there is no agent that reconciles these differences. It is because India allows

00:58:17.060 --> 00:58:22.420
[Guest]: people to express multiple identities. It is because the Indian state identifies the

00:58:22.420 --> 00:58:28.420
[Guest]: fact that individuals are hybrids. We are repositories of multiple identities. We cannot

00:58:28.420 --> 00:58:34.360
[Guest]: be reduced to one identity. And we are allowed to express all aspects of our identity that

00:58:34.360 --> 00:58:41.320
[Guest]: India thrives. And when you try to reduce individuals as Pakistan has done to one identity,

00:58:41.320 --> 00:58:48.180
[Guest]: that is a recipe for calamity. And one of the most interesting things that you're witnessing

00:58:48.180 --> 00:58:55.020
[Guest]: today is Muslims are at the forefront of the fight to protect, to save the constitution,

00:58:55.020 --> 00:59:00.860
[Guest]: to save the country. For five decades, they have been denigrated as a fifth column. They've

00:59:00.860 --> 00:59:06.660
[Guest]: been produced as traitors. They have been asked to account for the partition of India.

00:59:06.660 --> 00:59:10.860
[Guest]: And today they are on the streets and their song is the national anthem, their standard

00:59:10.860 --> 00:59:15.980
[Guest]: is the national flag, and their sacred book is the constitution of India. It is the Hindu,

00:59:15.980 --> 00:59:21.300
[Guest]: the self-pitying Hindu majority that is actually desecrating the constitution, that is actually

00:59:21.300 --> 00:59:22.300
[Guest]: denigrating the flag.

00:59:22.300 --> 00:59:24.700
[Guest]: That is actually fighting Jinnah's battle.

00:59:24.700 --> 00:59:30.420
[Guest]: That is actually finishing the business that Jinnah started us on. That is trying to complete

00:59:30.420 --> 00:59:34.700
[Guest]: the business of partition and turn India into a Hindu version of Pakistan. What did Jinnah

00:59:34.700 --> 00:59:39.340
[Guest]: say? Jinnah said that Hindus and Muslims are two nations who are fundamentally immiscible.

00:59:39.340 --> 00:59:44.300
[Guest]: They cannot co-exist together. They must have separate states. That is what Jinnah got.

00:59:44.300 --> 00:59:50.860
[Guest]: And India said, no, that's not what India is. You know, India is a multi-ethnic, multicultural,

00:59:50.860 --> 00:59:55.300
[Guest]: multiracial society, and we will prove that we can survive as one.

00:59:55.300 --> 01:00:00.460
[Guest]: And Narendra Modi's politics, the BJP's politics, the politics of the RSS is really a tribute

01:00:00.460 --> 01:00:06.660
[Guest]: to the vision of Jinnah. They keep telling Muslims, you know, Asad Awaisi, my MP, told

01:00:06.660 --> 01:00:11.260
[Guest]: me that, you know, one of the things that really makes him weep in private is when people

01:00:11.260 --> 01:00:14.260
[Guest]: tell him to go to Pakistan.

01:00:14.260 --> 01:00:21.580
[Guest]: And who belongs in Pakistan? Is it the people who fly the national flag, who take pride

01:00:21.580 --> 01:00:26.380
[Guest]: in being Indian, who put their lives on the line to remain in India, or the people who

01:00:26.380 --> 01:00:31.100
[Guest]: hate what India is, who hate their compatriots and want to remake India into something that

01:00:31.100 --> 01:00:35.660
[Guest]: India is fundamentally not? Who hates India more? Is it the Muslims of India or the people

01:00:35.660 --> 01:00:39.260
[Guest]: who currently are in power in India? The answer is quite obvious.

01:00:39.260 --> 01:00:42.020
[Amit Varma]: That's a wonderful way of putting it. I mean, who should go to Pakistan? Modi should go

01:00:42.020 --> 01:00:46.260
[Guest]: to Pakistan. If you put this to him, he would say, been there, attended the wedding.

01:00:46.260 --> 01:00:49.740
[Guest]: And he enjoyed it. He loved it. He kept his own cabinet in the dark when he was flying

01:00:49.740 --> 01:00:56.420
[Guest]: to Pakistan. Pakistan was really created for people who love homogeneity, who love people,

01:00:56.420 --> 01:01:01.420
[Guest]: who like, who think of human beings as milk, and they like to homogenize humans.

01:01:01.420 --> 01:01:06.460
[Guest]: The RSS really belongs in Pakistan. You know, Pakistan is the ideal environment for them.

01:01:06.460 --> 01:01:07.620
[Amit Varma]: It's custom made for them.

01:01:07.620 --> 01:01:13.420
[Amit Varma]: And this is probably a subject for a different episode entirely. But I think there is also

01:01:13.420 --> 01:01:18.180
[Amit Varma]: a clash between the state of Pakistan and this founding idea of Pakistan and the society

01:01:18.180 --> 01:01:23.140
[Amit Varma]: and the people of Pakistan, who I would say are more tolerant and inclusive and welcoming

01:01:23.140 --> 01:01:26.060
[Amit Varma]: than they are otherwise sort of given credit for.

01:01:26.060 --> 01:01:32.100
[Amit Varma]: My next question to you is this, that both of us delight in and perhaps even are proud

01:01:32.100 --> 01:01:38.120
[Amit Varma]: of this kind of lived secularism, this wholehearted embracing of diversity. But is there a difference

01:01:38.120 --> 01:01:43.340
[Amit Varma]: between this kind of social lived secularism and the political secularism that the Congress

01:01:43.340 --> 01:01:45.460
[Amit Varma]: Party embodied?

01:01:45.460 --> 01:01:50.580
[Guest]: So that political secularism Congress Party embodied was not a rejection of faith. It

01:01:50.580 --> 01:01:56.300
[Guest]: was a neutrality and it allowed all religions to express themselves. But here is the problem.

01:01:56.300 --> 01:02:01.420
[Guest]: Here is the flaw in that plan. This flaw is not an invitation to dismantle secularism.

01:02:01.420 --> 01:02:08.620
[Guest]: It's merely a statement of fact. Hinduism is both a faith and a culture and India is

01:02:08.620 --> 01:02:15.260
[Guest]: overwhelmingly Hindu. So it was bound to be the case that Hinduism would eclipse other

01:02:15.260 --> 01:02:20.180
[Guest]: religions in its expression when it was reflected, when its values were reflected by the state,

01:02:20.180 --> 01:02:26.540
[Guest]: when the state allowed different religions to make claims on it. So if you go to places,

01:02:26.540 --> 01:02:31.500
[Guest]: if you go to government buildings, you will find pictures of Hindu deities and Shashi

01:02:31.500 --> 01:02:37.740
[Guest]: Tharoor has a line in his book. He says, you know, Hindu rituals were performed at the

01:02:37.740 --> 01:02:42.460
[Guest]: opening of buildings when foundation stones were laid down and Muslims often accepted

01:02:42.460 --> 01:02:48.700
[Guest]: that in the same way that teetotallers accept alcohol at parties in the West. I spoke to

01:02:48.700 --> 01:02:54.380
[Guest]: several Muslims in Hyderabad some years ago. Actually, it seems that they don't. They feel

01:02:54.380 --> 01:02:59.060
[Guest]: an element of resentment, but they don't voice that resentment because they feel if they

01:02:59.060 --> 01:03:04.060
[Guest]: do, they'll be seen as difficult people. They'll be seen as, you know, ungrateful Muslims.

01:03:04.060 --> 01:03:09.620
[Guest]: So we haven't been able to strike that balance. I personally haven't figured out how, you

01:03:09.620 --> 01:03:16.780
[Guest]: know, I would like personally to see a secularity that rejects religion altogether, that politics

01:03:16.780 --> 01:03:23.340
[Guest]: is a fear in which religion has no business. That would be really ideal, but I know for

01:03:23.340 --> 01:03:28.980
[Guest]: various reasons that may not be practicable in India. But I also look on Lal Bahadur Shastri

01:03:28.980 --> 01:03:35.820
[Guest]: as a great exponent of Indian secularism. He was invited by a journalist from the Illustrated

01:03:35.820 --> 01:03:39.660
[Guest]: Weekly of India to talk about his religion when he became the leader of the Congress

01:03:39.660 --> 01:03:45.620
[Guest]: Party. And Shastri was a very religious man and his answer was very curt. He said, I'm

01:03:45.620 --> 01:03:50.740
[Guest]: the Prime Minister of India and I will not discuss my religion because there are people

01:03:50.740 --> 01:03:54.620
[Guest]: who do not belong to my religion. I'm also their Prime Minister and I do not wish to

01:03:54.620 --> 01:03:59.340
[Guest]: alienate them or make them feel that they cannot trust me because I do not, because

01:03:59.340 --> 01:04:04.540
[Guest]: I practice a different faith. My faith is my faith. It's my private business. I wish

01:04:04.540 --> 01:04:08.100
[Guest]: every Prime Minister would say that. I wish every Prime Minister would make it a point

01:04:08.100 --> 01:04:14.820
[Guest]: to remind our press, to remind people who invite politicians to exhibit their religious

01:04:14.820 --> 01:04:20.420
[Guest]: faith, to tell them that, you know, that is my private business. By all means, go and

01:04:20.420 --> 01:04:26.540
[Guest]: practice your faith. But for the duration that I occupy this high office, I will keep

01:04:26.540 --> 01:04:31.580
[Guest]: my faith private. I will keep my religion private. I will not give up my faith. I will

01:04:31.580 --> 01:04:35.340
[Guest]: go to the temple, I'll go to church, I'll go to mosque, but I'll do it in my private

01:04:35.340 --> 01:04:38.860
[Guest]: time. I will not let that impinge on my public role.

01:04:38.860 --> 01:04:43.180
[Amit Varma]: I couldn't agree more. And I didn't know this about Shastri and it's a very statesman

01:04:43.180 --> 01:04:48.340
[Amit Varma]: like thing. And it's also telling that in his personal life, he embraced his Hinduness.

01:04:48.340 --> 01:04:52.300
[Amit Varma]: He was, as I referred to earlier, you could say that he was a Hindu nationalist leader

01:04:52.300 --> 01:04:57.820
[Amit Varma]: within the Congress. But when holding a constitutional office, he kept religion out of it, which

01:04:57.820 --> 01:05:04.260
[Amit Varma]: is sort of the way secularism should be. And to sort of go on further, you have also written

01:05:04.260 --> 01:05:10.820
[Amit Varma]: in your book about how, you know, while we bemoan how the Hindu nationalists in power

01:05:10.820 --> 01:05:16.340
[Amit Varma]: today are trying to rewrite history, the fact is that this was also done by the secularists,

01:05:16.340 --> 01:05:21.220
[Amit Varma]: that there was a project of rewriting history to wipe away what happened in the medieval

01:05:21.220 --> 01:05:24.580
[Amit Varma]: ages and that we need not have done that. Can you elaborate a bit on that?

01:05:24.580 --> 01:05:32.260
[Guest]: Yeah, that is one of the most contentious parts of heritage. We need to accept that

01:05:32.260 --> 01:05:38.940
[Guest]: the arrival of Islam in India, certainly in North India, was braided together with extraordinary

01:05:38.940 --> 01:05:45.620
[Guest]: violence. And it was accompanied by the destruction, the wholesale destruction of India's heritage,

01:05:45.620 --> 01:05:50.340
[Guest]: cultural heritage. In many places, there are no traces of the Hindu-Buddhist past of India.

01:05:50.340 --> 01:05:57.760
[Guest]: How do you deal with that past? How do you talk about it? We haven't figured out a way

01:05:57.760 --> 01:06:04.380
[Guest]: of talking about that. There is something called memory and that memory is embedded

01:06:04.380 --> 01:06:10.660
[Guest]: in people's marrow. People have inherited memories of loss from prior generations. There

01:06:10.660 --> 01:06:13.980
[Guest]: are ballads of dispossession that have passed down from generation to generation. People

01:06:13.980 --> 01:06:22.540
[Guest]: know that some horror occurred. I was in Varangal in Telangana some years ago and this was in

01:06:22.540 --> 01:06:28.140
[Guest]: the 12th century one of the marvels of the world. You know, it was, you know, it traded

01:06:28.140 --> 01:06:31.660
[Guest]: diamonds with Europe. Marco Polo visited and he said, you know, I've never seen wealth

01:06:31.660 --> 01:06:37.360
[Guest]: like this anywhere. And some tragedy happened there, you know, when Alauddin Khilji sent

01:06:37.360 --> 01:06:42.860
[Guest]: his men. People still remember that eight centuries later, seven centuries later and

01:06:42.860 --> 01:06:49.540
[Guest]: they are still shaped by that memory but they cannot quite express what that tragedy was.

01:06:49.540 --> 01:06:53.700
[Guest]: And when they can't, when there is a vacuum in their memory, that vacuum will be filled

01:06:53.700 --> 01:07:00.460
[Guest]: by the garbage purveyed by the current dispensation. So, I think it's best to be honest about

01:07:00.460 --> 01:07:06.460
[Guest]: our history, to say that, listen, horrible things happened in the past. We accept that,

01:07:06.460 --> 01:07:12.300
[Guest]: we move on from it. Instead of doing that, what the secular establishment did is it found

01:07:12.300 --> 01:07:18.100
[Guest]: complex ways of skirting around the issue. So, if you pick up a book by some of our most

01:07:18.100 --> 01:07:24.760
[Guest]: distinguished historians, you will put down the book none the wiser. You will not actually

01:07:24.760 --> 01:07:30.700
[Guest]: understand what happened in the past. There is such complex prose, jargon is piled upon

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:38.300
[Guest]: jargon to actually evade the reality of what happened. We haven't dealt with that past

01:07:38.300 --> 01:07:42.900
[Guest]: and we haven't actually figured out a way of talking about that past. We've come up

01:07:42.900 --> 01:07:49.220
[Guest]: with gravity-defying ways of dealing with it, of discussing it. If you look at Pakistan,

01:07:49.220 --> 01:07:53.580
[Guest]: I've been to Pakistan. If you talk to people in Pakistan, they're quite open about what

01:07:53.580 --> 01:08:00.620
[Guest]: their history was, how India was invaded several times. In India, we haven't talked about that

01:08:00.620 --> 01:08:07.980
[Guest]: and we need to find a mature way to discuss that. Otherwise, we, in place of history,

01:08:07.980 --> 01:08:14.180
[Guest]: we will have things like Indians colonized Mars, Indians invented the first F-16 jet

01:08:14.180 --> 01:08:22.060
[Guest]: or, you know, gold can be mined from cow dung. Stuff like that actually finds an audience

01:08:22.060 --> 01:08:28.420
[Guest]: because there is nothing else there. And people go to school in India. I've met, I made it

01:08:28.420 --> 01:08:32.540
[Guest]: my mission five years ago to go and meet as many school children as I could and talk to

01:08:32.540 --> 01:08:37.300
[Guest]: them about what they knew of history. And it was extremely distressing to find that

01:08:37.300 --> 01:08:42.260
[Guest]: they came out of school without a linear understanding of their past. They did not know what happened.

01:08:42.260 --> 01:08:48.140
[Guest]: They would say, they would use this phrase, in those days, you know, they'd say terrible

01:08:48.140 --> 01:08:52.780
[Guest]: things happened, but they didn't really know what had happened. And when you don't know

01:08:52.780 --> 01:08:56.980
[Guest]: what had happened, when you don't know your own history, you're bound to become susceptible

01:08:56.980 --> 01:09:00.940
[Guest]: to distortions of history. And that is what we're seeing happen. You know, there are people

01:09:00.940 --> 01:09:08.440
[Guest]: who've said, let's burn books. Subramanian Swami invited goons in the BJP to burn histories

01:09:08.440 --> 01:09:12.780
[Guest]: written by secular historians. It's very important to remember that secular historians did what

01:09:12.780 --> 01:09:19.660
[Guest]: they did from a very noble motivation. It was to deny ammunition to Hindu nationalists.

01:09:19.660 --> 01:09:24.940
[Guest]: But the tragedy of that is rather than denying ammunition to Hindu nationalists, they enabled

01:09:24.940 --> 01:09:29.860
[Guest]: Hindu nationalists to weaponize history. And we need to be absolutely honest about our

01:09:29.860 --> 01:09:34.300
[Guest]: history. That is the only way we can escape the punishing torment of history.

01:09:34.300 --> 01:09:38.060
[Amit Varma]: So I have a couple of related musings. But before that, a couple of quotes from your

01:09:38.060 --> 01:09:43.780
[Amit Varma]: book, where you sort of expressed all of this really well. First, quote, it was a mission

01:09:43.780 --> 01:09:47.820
[Amit Varma]: of secular, quote unquote secular, it was a mission of secular historians and public

01:09:47.820 --> 01:09:53.620
[Amit Varma]: intellectuals of India to locate mundane causes for carnage by religious zealots. And later

01:09:53.620 --> 01:09:58.780
[Amit Varma]: you say, all imperialism is vicious, but that is not the standard adopted by India's secular

01:09:58.780 --> 01:10:03.900
[Amit Varma]: historians. And again, later you say imperialism, in other words, was destructive only when

01:10:03.900 --> 01:10:09.660
[Amit Varma]: Europeans did it. When Asians did it, it was a cultural exchange program, stop quote. And

01:10:09.660 --> 01:10:15.060
[Amit Varma]: your sort of conclusion here is, quote, the secular establishments squandered a rare opening

01:10:15.060 --> 01:10:20.540
[Amit Varma]: in the early decades of the Republic to heal that wound by supplying Indians a forthright

01:10:20.540 --> 01:10:26.900
[Amit Varma]: accounting of the history, stop quote. And my sort of related musings are, one, the fear

01:10:26.900 --> 01:10:32.700
[Amit Varma]: that this came from is actually in some ways a modern fear that description of a particular

01:10:32.700 --> 01:10:38.140
[Amit Varma]: sort necessarily implies prescription of another sort. And we see it in modern times as well.

01:10:38.140 --> 01:10:45.060
[Amit Varma]: For example, they feared that by saying that Muslim invaders did XYZ, that will implicitly

01:10:45.060 --> 01:10:49.780
[Amit Varma]: be a prescription for revenge or whatever. And you see that in modern times, for example,

01:10:49.780 --> 01:10:54.700
[Amit Varma]: in the way nature is treated by, you know, there's a certain denialism of science, where,

01:10:54.700 --> 01:11:02.980
[Amit Varma]: for example, if you point out differences between sexes or races, they are taken as

01:11:02.980 --> 01:11:07.420
[Amit Varma]: not just as statements of differences, but as statements of value and prescriptions on

01:11:07.420 --> 01:11:12.780
[Amit Varma]: treating differently, and the two don't necessarily follow. And my other thought there is that

01:11:12.780 --> 01:11:19.560
[Amit Varma]: this also comes from a notion of the Congress and others, and I'm not passing a value judgment

01:11:19.560 --> 01:11:24.780
[Amit Varma]: on this notion of whether there is something to it or not, is that history is alive, in

01:11:24.780 --> 01:11:30.100
[Amit Varma]: a sense that it needs to be remedied. Now, we don't just look at it as something in the

01:11:30.100 --> 01:11:34.900
[Amit Varma]: past. And I disagree with this notion. But and Congress, it would be said did believe

01:11:34.900 --> 01:11:39.860
[Amit Varma]: this in the context of say, caste, where they were, of course, you know, we've had all of

01:11:39.860 --> 01:11:45.620
[Amit Varma]: this caste injustice. And we must, for example, reverse discriminate to sort it out or sort

01:11:45.620 --> 01:11:50.420
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, which plays into a whole different kind of identity politics, or, you know, in

01:11:50.420 --> 01:11:55.380
[Amit Varma]: terms of, for example, land distribution, that we must do land redistribution. So through

01:11:55.380 --> 01:11:59.340
[Amit Varma]: both of these, and again, I'm not passing a value judgment on either of these, and they

01:11:59.340 --> 01:12:03.300
[Amit Varma]: might even be necessary correctives. But in both of these cases, a Congress seems to be

01:12:03.300 --> 01:12:08.220
[Amit Varma]: taking the philosophical position that things that have happened in the past should be remedied

01:12:08.220 --> 01:12:13.580
[Amit Varma]: in modern times. And if they then believe in this, then this sort of historical this

01:12:13.580 --> 01:12:19.020
[Amit Varma]: treatment of history seems rational, I would say wrong, I agree with you on why it is wrong,

01:12:19.020 --> 01:12:24.580
[Amit Varma]: because you eventually you've ended up helping these guys to weaponize the part of the history

01:12:24.580 --> 01:12:28.780
[Amit Varma]: that we tried to erase out. But it seems to me and I'm just thinking aloud that that is

01:12:28.780 --> 01:12:30.660
[Guest]: where the impulse kind of comes from.

01:12:30.660 --> 01:12:35.500
[Guest]: I think in this case, it would have been difficult because the elite representation in the Muslim

01:12:35.500 --> 01:12:41.680
[Guest]: community, the elite segment of the Muslim community fled to Pakistan after partition.

01:12:41.680 --> 01:12:47.580
[Guest]: So the remaining, the remainder of Muslim community in India was actually quite marginal

01:12:47.580 --> 01:12:54.300
[Guest]: to the power of the community. So it would have been extremely perverse for them to sort

01:12:54.300 --> 01:13:00.140
[Guest]: of try to remedy a historical wrong by blaming anybody. When you talk about caste, to this

01:13:00.140 --> 01:13:06.740
[Guest]: day, the upper castes in India are still powerful, that is where they still hold power. Whereas

01:13:06.740 --> 01:13:10.580
[Guest]: that was not true of the Muslim community in India, and it would have been extremely

01:13:10.580 --> 01:13:14.980
[Guest]: cruel and perverse of them to point the finger at them. And then how would you remedy that?

01:13:14.980 --> 01:13:19.340
[Guest]: You know, what would the prescription then be? Would you would you transfer their non

01:13:19.340 --> 01:13:23.580
[Guest]: existent properties to Hindus who already had properties and whom would you give the

01:13:23.580 --> 01:13:24.580
[Amit Varma]: property to?

01:13:24.580 --> 01:13:29.100
[Amit Varma]: The thing is, that is exactly what's happening today. And it was that the fear of that happening

01:13:29.100 --> 01:13:35.020
[Amit Varma]: back then that led the Congress to do this. Yeah. And obviously, you have unintended consequences

01:13:35.020 --> 01:13:40.260
[Amit Varma]: for everything. And these intuitive solutions of, you know, correcting history don't necessarily

01:13:40.260 --> 01:13:41.260
[Guest]: work.

01:13:41.260 --> 01:13:46.700
[Guest]: I'm merely distinguishing caste and religion. Sure. And I will just say about religion,

01:13:46.700 --> 01:13:55.060
[Guest]: Congress had tremendous moral authority, and it had it enjoyed massive goodwill among the

01:13:55.060 --> 01:14:00.660
[Guest]: people of India. And this was a time at which after the elections in 1951, for instance,

01:14:00.660 --> 01:14:05.980
[Guest]: Congress was so powerful, it had such authority to shape India, and what Indians were going

01:14:05.980 --> 01:14:11.580
[Guest]: to be, I think it could have used that authority to be honest about India's history, because

01:14:11.580 --> 01:14:15.580
[Guest]: that was the opening. That was the moment at which you could do it. And you could do

01:14:15.580 --> 01:14:22.700
[Guest]: it in a way that spoke, frankly, about the historical wrongs, without actually prescribing

01:14:22.700 --> 01:14:30.060
[Guest]: retribution. And that is the moment that was squandered, that opening was squandered. Instead,

01:14:30.060 --> 01:14:38.140
[Guest]: what we had was high-minded, incomprehensible history that actually papered over what happened

01:14:38.140 --> 01:14:42.780
[Guest]: in the medieval era. That I will cite, I don't have it in front of me, but from memory, I'll

01:14:42.780 --> 01:14:47.900
[Guest]: cite one of the textbooks I read. It says that when the Portuguese came into India,

01:14:47.900 --> 01:14:55.620
[Guest]: you know, they presided over conversions of people and Indian society altered fundamentally.

01:14:55.620 --> 01:15:01.220
[Guest]: They were horrible. They were uniquely vicious people. The very same textbook, a paragraph

01:15:01.220 --> 01:15:05.740
[Guest]: apart, says that when Muslims came to India, there was no fundamental cultural shift, and

01:15:05.740 --> 01:15:10.780
[Guest]: they were tolerant, and they did not inflict any injuries on the people of India. That

01:15:10.780 --> 01:15:15.660
[Guest]: is infantilizing. And eventually, people are going to question that. And when they question

01:15:15.660 --> 01:15:21.460
[Guest]: that, they will feel betrayed. And when they feel betrayed, they will become uniquely susceptible

01:15:21.460 --> 01:15:28.220
[Guest]: to the drivel pumped out, the anger pumped out by the Hindu nationalists. And that is

01:15:28.220 --> 01:15:35.300
[Guest]: what is happening right now. I myself felt some of that rage when I first read about,

01:15:35.300 --> 01:15:39.220
[Guest]: you know, when I first picked up first-hand sources, because I had a very secular upbringing,

01:15:39.220 --> 01:15:43.180
[Guest]: extremely secular upbringing. I had a secular upbringing to the extent that we didn't celebrate

01:15:43.180 --> 01:15:46.940
[Guest]: Hindu holidays, because we thought it might be offensive to our Muslim neighbors, and

01:15:46.940 --> 01:15:52.300
[Guest]: we lived in predominantly Muslim communities. So, it could be an almost comical reaction

01:15:52.300 --> 01:15:56.100
[Guest]: to that kind of upbringing to become a Hindu nationalist. So, you must always keep your

01:15:56.100 --> 01:16:04.300
[Guest]: antennae up and try to stop yourself from becoming tempted by that release offered by

01:16:04.300 --> 01:16:13.500
[Guest]: Hindu nationalism. And yet, what happened in medieval India was so bloody and so horrendous

01:16:13.500 --> 01:16:23.780
[Guest]: that unless you find a way of distilling that past and talking about it, you will not be

01:16:23.780 --> 01:16:32.540
[Guest]: able to delegitimize the vendors of untruths who are now in power.

01:16:32.540 --> 01:16:35.860
[Amit Varma]: This reminds me of something that, you know, a friend of mine, Sadanand Hume, was on this

01:16:35.860 --> 01:16:41.260
[Amit Varma]: show a few months back. And he told me about this almost dissonant experience he would

01:16:41.260 --> 01:16:48.220
[Amit Varma]: have at TV studios, where he would find that people arguing for the Hindu nationalist would

01:16:48.220 --> 01:16:54.420
[Amit Varma]: almost have this warped sense of time in history. And in the sense that they will refer to something

01:16:54.420 --> 01:16:59.140
[Amit Varma]: that happened yesterday, like I went to lunch at so and so place, and something that happened

01:16:59.140 --> 01:17:03.660
[Amit Varma]: 500 years ago, in almost the same breath as if there was absolutely no difference with

01:17:03.660 --> 01:17:09.700
[Amit Varma]: them. And would that warp sort of view on history simply be, you know, is it partly

01:17:09.700 --> 01:17:15.260
[Amit Varma]: a consequence of this eliding of history where you're taught it in a linear way in school,

01:17:15.260 --> 01:17:20.660
[Amit Varma]: and because all of this is absent, they internalize it in a different way? Or is it just that

01:17:20.660 --> 01:17:21.660
[Guest]: they're ignorant and uneducated?

01:17:21.660 --> 01:17:29.700
[Guest]: See, there is this idea that Hindus are a defeated people. And somehow, people respond

01:17:29.700 --> 01:17:40.180
[Guest]: to ideas of revenge. Revenging history is a very popular concept. The temple which stood

01:17:40.180 --> 01:17:46.060
[Guest]: on the site of Babri Masjid, if it stood at all, was demolished half a millennium ago.

01:17:46.060 --> 01:17:54.820
[Guest]: And yet people respond to it, because for them, it is a way of when you feel defeated,

01:17:54.820 --> 01:18:01.540
[Guest]: you will want to acquire the dignity that was taken away from you through any means.

01:18:01.540 --> 01:18:08.900
[Guest]: We may dislike it. We may find faults with that. But there is an emotional response that

01:18:08.900 --> 01:18:14.780
[Guest]: is tremendously powerful. When you go to people, when people feel they've been wronged, when

01:18:14.780 --> 01:18:21.140
[Guest]: people feel that their heritage was destroyed, and when people feel that there is a vacuum,

01:18:21.140 --> 01:18:26.140
[Guest]: nobody talked about it, they will respond to cries for justice, even if it happened

01:18:26.140 --> 01:18:32.380
[Guest]: a millennium ago. And you will, you can't run away from that. All around us is evidence

01:18:32.380 --> 01:18:33.380
[Guest]: of that.

01:18:33.380 --> 01:18:37.180
[Amit Varma]: And you don't even have to go millennium ago. I mean, the thing is, if we enter a vicious

01:18:37.180 --> 01:18:42.300
[Amit Varma]: circle of violence and radicalism, you don't really need to go that far back. I mean, you

01:18:42.300 --> 01:18:45.940
[Amit Varma]: know, a Hindu right winger today can point with some justification to what happened in

01:18:45.940 --> 01:18:51.300
[Amit Varma]: the Kashmiri pundits, for example, in the early 90s and point to that as cause enough

01:18:51.300 --> 01:18:56.500
[Amit Varma]: for his radicalism. How do we break out of these cycles of violence? Like one of the

01:18:56.500 --> 01:19:02.800
[Amit Varma]: very interesting things you sort of pointed out in your book is that this movement may

01:19:02.800 --> 01:19:07.620
[Amit Varma]: be incompetent in government, but it's peerless in opposition. You know, I mean, incompetent

01:19:07.620 --> 01:19:11.220
[Amit Varma]: in government, obviously, you can see what has happened, though I think Vajpayee was

01:19:11.220 --> 01:19:15.100
[Amit Varma]: a much better Prime Minister than Modi is, but that's a different story. But incompetent

01:19:15.100 --> 01:19:18.780
[Amit Varma]: in government, but peerless in opposition. And the thing is, it's very easy, like the

01:19:18.780 --> 01:19:23.220
[Amit Varma]: Congress is finding out to be in opposition in the sense that you can then be perennially

01:19:23.220 --> 01:19:28.180
[Amit Varma]: virtuous depending on how you define virtue when you're not faced with the everyday reality

01:19:28.180 --> 01:19:31.780
[Amit Varma]: of governing and actually running a country, a challenge that these guys haven't even really

01:19:31.780 --> 01:19:35.980
[Amit Varma]: taken seriously. Otherwise, they would have behaved more statesmanly, like say Shastri

01:19:35.980 --> 01:19:42.180
[Amit Varma]: did, a person they have tried to co-opt, rather than behaving in the ways that they have.

01:19:42.180 --> 01:19:47.580
[Amit Varma]: And that would then seem to indicate that if you are against the Hindu nationalist movement,

01:19:47.580 --> 01:19:52.540
[Amit Varma]: and you do believe in our natural secularism, the left secularism, our tolerance to sort

01:19:52.540 --> 01:19:57.580
[Amit Varma]: of express itself and take over again, then a political victory isn't enough, because

01:19:57.580 --> 01:20:04.040
[Amit Varma]: these guys are going to continue. And especially because what you also see is that now it is

01:20:04.040 --> 01:20:08.780
[Amit Varma]: actually a moot issue, what kind of history is taught in schools, because I think more

01:20:08.780 --> 01:20:14.820
[Amit Varma]: people learn from what is colloquially referred to as a WhatsApp university.

01:20:14.820 --> 01:20:18.540
[Guest]: This project of distilling our history is not for the Hindu nationalists. They don't

01:20:18.540 --> 01:20:23.740
[Guest]: have the intellectual equipment to do that. This is, to the extent that there is a prescription

01:20:23.740 --> 01:20:29.580
[Guest]: in my book, it's for the secularists among us. I'm speaking to people like you. I'm speaking

01:20:29.580 --> 01:20:30.580
[Guest]: to people like Sadanand.

01:20:30.580 --> 01:20:33.300
[Guest]: But we are the converted.

01:20:33.300 --> 01:20:34.860
[Amit Varma]: In what way? Sorry.

01:20:34.860 --> 01:20:36.480
[Guest]: In the sense we are secular already.

01:20:36.480 --> 01:20:40.780
[Guest]: We are secular already, but I'm saying in order to save the secular cause, in order

01:20:40.780 --> 01:20:45.140
[Guest]: to convert the people who aren't secular, in order to bring them back, in order to rescue

01:20:45.140 --> 01:20:49.140
[Guest]: India, in order to save India, in order to ensure India's future, we need to be honest

01:20:49.140 --> 01:20:52.460
[Guest]: about our past. That is, to the extent that there is a prescription in my book, I think

01:20:52.460 --> 01:20:56.980
[Guest]: we should find mature ways of talking about our past. Because WhatsApp university, quote

01:20:56.980 --> 01:21:01.760
[Guest]: unquote, is popular today, doesn't mean that we pack our bags and give up. We find new

01:21:01.760 --> 01:21:08.620
[Guest]: ways to fight. We can't admit defeat to these people. We can't let this distortion of history

01:21:08.620 --> 01:21:15.060
[Guest]: become the norm in India. We've become the world's laughingstock as a result of it. And

01:21:15.060 --> 01:21:20.120
[Guest]: if we take pride, you began this segment by talking about taking pride in being Indian.

01:21:20.120 --> 01:21:24.940
[Guest]: And if we are to take pride in being Indian, we must fight back against people who make

01:21:24.940 --> 01:21:30.340
[Guest]: a mockery of Indianness. And that is the very precise argument I was trying to make in the

01:21:30.340 --> 01:21:31.340
[Guest]: book.

01:21:31.340 --> 01:21:35.940
[Guest]: One more thing, Amit, is that these people will never, will never give up in the sense

01:21:35.940 --> 01:21:40.440
[Guest]: that if they exhaust one cause, they will find another cause. Because what is fueling

01:21:40.440 --> 01:21:47.180
[Guest]: them now is not undoing an historical wrong. What is fueling them is a sense of self-pity.

01:21:47.180 --> 01:21:51.740
[Guest]: And there is nothing more damaging, destructive than self-pity.

01:21:51.740 --> 01:21:56.060
[Amit Varma]: So here's the thing, it's far easier to build a movement and sustain a movement and make

01:21:56.060 --> 01:22:02.740
[Amit Varma]: a movement reach critical mass on hate rather than, you know, better emotions. Similarly,

01:22:02.740 --> 01:22:07.020
[Amit Varma]: victimhood is very appealing in politics, whether it's from the right wing or the left

01:22:07.020 --> 01:22:12.000
[Amit Varma]: wing, you know, and one of the common things to many populist movements is that it involves

01:22:12.000 --> 01:22:17.340
[Amit Varma]: a majority invoking its own victimhood, which is kind of absurd. I mean, given that, you

01:22:17.340 --> 01:22:21.900
[Amit Varma]: know, the Muslim population in India is far more disempowered than they were before partition

01:22:21.900 --> 01:22:26.940
[Amit Varma]: and they are far poorer than Hindus for, you know, for us to still claim that victimhood

01:22:26.940 --> 01:22:32.260
[Amit Varma]: is slightly bizarre to me. Now, given all of these things that you're going to motivate

01:22:32.260 --> 01:22:38.740
[Amit Varma]: a movement more on negative emotions and on positive emotions, which perhaps also explains

01:22:38.740 --> 01:22:46.020
[Amit Varma]: the trend in recent times of voter turnout being far higher for right wing populist movements

01:22:46.020 --> 01:22:51.980
[Amit Varma]: than their opponents, because, you know, stronger motivations from, oh, you know, Hindu khatre

01:22:51.980 --> 01:22:55.700
[Amit Varma]: and therefore you go out and vote, rather than let's all live together peacefully, which

01:22:55.700 --> 01:23:01.620
[Amit Varma]: so how do you react to that as a challenge? And also, what do you think of the contemporary

01:23:01.620 --> 01:23:06.140
[Amit Varma]: protests which are going on? I mean, you know, as we are recording this as a start of February,

01:23:06.140 --> 01:23:10.500
[Amit Varma]: this Shaheen Bagh happening, there are spontaneous protests all across the country. I think my

01:23:10.500 --> 01:23:15.220
[Amit Varma]: friend Prem Panikkar posted a map on Twitter where he had pins on a map of India, all over

01:23:15.220 --> 01:23:19.460
[Amit Varma]: showing that the and these are not centrally planned. These are not coming from one place.

01:23:19.460 --> 01:23:25.420
[Amit Varma]: These are spontaneous protests that are erupting with ordinary people using technology, which

01:23:25.420 --> 01:23:30.260
[Amit Varma]: is not something I would have foreseen a couple of months ago. You know, I was pretty I had

01:23:30.260 --> 01:23:35.260
[Amit Varma]: given up a lot of hope. But now this is happening. What's your sense of this?

01:23:35.260 --> 01:23:40.940
[Guest]: So your first question was about the difficulty of combating the right with something more

01:23:40.940 --> 01:23:48.700
[Guest]: virtuous. And your second question was about the organic eruption of protests built on

01:23:48.700 --> 01:23:53.820
[Guest]: upholding the virtue of the Constitution. So in answer to the first question, Raymond

01:23:53.820 --> 01:23:57.980
[Guest]: Aron wrote something during Algeria's fight for independence. He said, you know, it is

01:23:57.980 --> 01:24:04.460
[Guest]: the lesson of the 20th century, that in the contest between passions and interests, passions

01:24:04.460 --> 01:24:10.260
[Guest]: will always defeat interests. You know, it is a mistake to think that interests can trump

01:24:10.260 --> 01:24:18.300
[Guest]: passions. So we have a contest between passion and interest. Narendra Modi is demonstrably

01:24:18.300 --> 01:24:24.020
[Guest]: not good for you, good for your interests. This is the man who singed the economy. This

01:24:24.020 --> 01:24:28.940
[Guest]: is a man who presided over, as you put it, the largest single destruction of private

01:24:28.940 --> 01:24:37.860
[Guest]: property in human history, which was demonetization. And yet people reelected him because he appealed

01:24:37.860 --> 01:24:44.900
[Guest]: to and incited their passions. Now, how do you fight back? The fight back is right in

01:24:44.900 --> 01:24:53.780
[Guest]: front of us. What we are witnessing with CAA, with the protests against CAA and NRC, Shaheen

01:24:53.780 --> 01:24:57.340
[Guest]: Bagh and across the country. I've been to Shaheen Bagh. I spent time there. I've been

01:24:57.340 --> 01:25:04.260
[Guest]: to other protest sites. I've spoken to protesters. What you're witnessing is not just a response

01:25:04.260 --> 01:25:10.980
[Guest]: to this legislation. It is a belated eruption of grievances that piled up over five years.

01:25:10.980 --> 01:25:15.260
[Guest]: It is a belated response to demonetization. It is a belated response to unemployment.

01:25:15.260 --> 01:25:19.800
[Guest]: It is a belated response to the absence of smart cities. All the promises, every major

01:25:19.800 --> 01:25:27.040
[Guest]: promise made by Modi, every major developmental promise made by Modi is unfulfilled. Every

01:25:27.040 --> 01:25:32.340
[Guest]: major promise made to his religious base, his ideological base is fulfilled. Kashmir,

01:25:32.340 --> 01:25:43.580
[Guest]: Ram Janmabhoomi, now CAA. So, these are ordinary people protesting against the authoritarian

01:25:43.580 --> 01:25:50.860
[Guest]: turn of the government. And the trigger is the CAA legislation and the prospect of a

01:25:50.860 --> 01:25:58.060
[Guest]: nationwide registry of citizens. I look at these protests with great pride because they

01:25:58.060 --> 01:26:05.100
[Guest]: reveal to us that you began earlier this interview by asking me if, you know, about people who

01:26:05.100 --> 01:26:10.540
[Guest]: say that our constitution is an imposition. But what these protests reveal is the depths

01:26:10.540 --> 01:26:18.540
[Guest]: to which the content of the constitution has percolated. We are now a country of citizens

01:26:18.540 --> 01:26:23.760
[Guest]: and people are asserting their citizenly rights against a government that is denying them

01:26:23.760 --> 01:26:29.940
[Guest]: those rights. So, this is a moment, if Nehru was looking at us, he'd be very proud. This

01:26:29.940 --> 01:26:34.140
[Guest]: is, you know, in a moment of crisis, we have risen to the occasion. The people of India

01:26:34.140 --> 01:26:38.980
[Guest]: have risen to the occasion across the country. This is an organic uprising against this hideous

01:26:38.980 --> 01:26:45.380
[Guest]: regime. So, and what are they protesting for? They're protesting for the protection of the

01:26:45.380 --> 01:26:52.060
[Guest]: constitution against the assault of this government. But I also look at this protest with some

01:26:52.060 --> 01:27:01.140
[Guest]: pessimism because I fear that we overlook the extraordinary power of the prime minister.

01:27:01.140 --> 01:27:08.100
[Guest]: He's six months into his second term. He has a super majority in parliament. He has bottomless

01:27:08.100 --> 01:27:14.300
[Guest]: supplies of cash at his disposal. And I mentioned this fact because goons can be hired, cash

01:27:14.300 --> 01:27:19.620
[Guest]: can be given, protests can be disrupted and delegitimized. And the prime minister has

01:27:19.620 --> 01:27:25.660
[Guest]: means to do that. The prime minister also innovated the state. He destroyed autonomous

01:27:25.660 --> 01:27:34.820
[Guest]: state institutions in his first term. So, he is the master. He has total authority over

01:27:34.820 --> 01:27:41.300
[Guest]: the instruments of force. The police is completely under his thumb. Even the armed forces have

01:27:41.300 --> 01:27:47.340
[Guest]: been politicized. So, he has that raw power of the malicious raised by the Hindu nationalists

01:27:47.340 --> 01:27:53.540
[Guest]: over the past five decades are at his beck and call, but also the state institutions

01:27:53.540 --> 01:27:58.080
[Guest]: have completely caved. So, the prime minister is enormously powerful and he can crush these

01:27:58.080 --> 01:28:03.180
[Guest]: protesters at the time of his choosing. There are people who believe that because the international

01:28:03.180 --> 01:28:08.780
[Guest]: press is aggressively covering it, they have allies abroad. We should remember they do

01:28:08.780 --> 01:28:17.280
[Guest]: not have allies abroad. Foreign nations, foreign press will not sustain its coverage. You know,

01:28:17.280 --> 01:28:22.380
[Guest]: they have their own problems at home. You know, they will not focus their energies entirely

01:28:22.380 --> 01:28:27.820
[Guest]: on India and their ability to influence India's behavior is also very limited. Modi will eventually

01:28:27.820 --> 01:28:32.260
[Guest]: cease to care about what the world thinks about him. You know, if it's a question of

01:28:32.260 --> 01:28:37.420
[Guest]: his reputation on the world stage and power at home, he will choose power at home. So,

01:28:37.420 --> 01:28:42.540
[Guest]: it is important to remember that Modi in this contest, Modi is the more powerful person

01:28:42.540 --> 01:28:50.100
[Guest]: and nobody should doubt the power of the prime minister. But remember this, if these protests

01:28:50.100 --> 01:28:57.180
[Guest]: could either rescue India or they could be the swan song to the India that was, and if

01:28:57.180 --> 01:29:03.220
[Guest]: we lose India after this, if India goes to a point of no return, we can take pride in

01:29:03.220 --> 01:29:08.660
[Guest]: the fact that India didn't just give up. India didn't just fall on its knees when

01:29:08.660 --> 01:29:14.020
[Guest]: it faltered. India fought back and the fight back was extraordinary. And the fight back

01:29:14.020 --> 01:29:20.580
[Guest]: was beautiful. The fight back was inclusive. The fight back spoke for the values upon which

01:29:20.580 --> 01:29:26.980
[Guest]: this country was founded. And we, you know, we didn't go silently into the night. We

01:29:26.980 --> 01:29:31.820
[Guest]: raised our voice. This is something Indians can take tremendous pride in. But we must

01:29:31.820 --> 01:29:40.300
[Guest]: hope that there are remnants of democratic impulses in the prime minister and that he

01:29:40.300 --> 01:29:44.860
[Guest]: will listen to the people of India and that he will withdraw from this fight. He's never

01:29:44.860 --> 01:29:50.020
[Guest]: withdrawn. He's never lost a direct political fight in his life. But we have to hope that,

01:29:50.020 --> 01:29:56.420
[Guest]: you know, in this contest, the prime minister will be reined in by the vestiges of democratic

01:29:56.420 --> 01:30:00.300
[Amit Varma]: impulses in him. Yeah, we'll rage, rage against the dying of

01:30:00.300 --> 01:30:05.700
[Amit Varma]: the light. But I have sort of two questions. One of them is that this goes back to my earlier

01:30:05.700 --> 01:30:11.340
[Amit Varma]: point of the conception being flawed, not just the execution, like the fear that you

01:30:11.340 --> 01:30:16.580
[Amit Varma]: correctly express and that I share is that the power of the coercive state is way too

01:30:16.580 --> 01:30:20.260
[Amit Varma]: much. They can crush these protests anytime you want. That is unfortunately the case.

01:30:20.260 --> 01:30:24.700
[Amit Varma]: They can crush dissent anytime they want. The only reason someone like me hasn't been

01:30:24.700 --> 01:30:29.380
[Amit Varma]: crushed is because I'm too small and insignificant, but they can crush anybody anytime. So the

01:30:29.380 --> 01:30:33.700
[Amit Varma]: issue is with the coercive state itself. Like I did an episode with the historian Gyan Prakash

01:30:33.700 --> 01:30:38.060
[Amit Varma]: on the emergency where he pointed out that nothing that Indira Gandhi did during that

01:30:38.060 --> 01:30:43.300
[Amit Varma]: time was illegal or unconstitutional. That centralization of power which allowed her

01:30:43.300 --> 01:30:47.540
[Amit Varma]: to rule in such an autocratic way was written down in the constitution. And Gyan's point,

01:30:47.540 --> 01:30:52.980
[Amit Varma]: of course, was that the founders of the constitution sat down and framed the constitution in a

01:30:52.980 --> 01:30:57.900
[Amit Varma]: room in Delhi at a time where there were protests, there was violence across the country and

01:30:57.900 --> 01:31:02.460
[Amit Varma]: one was not sure whether the center can hold and therefore the centralized power. And Madhav

01:31:02.460 --> 01:31:07.900
[Amit Varma]: Khosla, of course, in his wonderful book, India's founding moment as a far greater sort

01:31:07.900 --> 01:31:13.340
[Amit Varma]: of a much finer narrative about how these decisions to centralize the state came about

01:31:13.340 --> 01:31:18.580
[Amit Varma]: and a lot of it makes incredible sense. But what it has also unleashed is that the coercive

01:31:18.580 --> 01:31:23.900
[Amit Varma]: state is way too powerful for democratic impulses to come through. Like right now, you said

01:31:23.900 --> 01:31:29.820
[Amit Varma]: that one hopes that Narendra Modi will, you know, listen to whatever vestiges of democratic

01:31:29.820 --> 01:31:34.340
[Amit Varma]: impulses are left within him. But I'm like, why should we hope for a person's, the better

01:31:34.340 --> 01:31:38.820
[Amit Varma]: angels of a person's nature to come to our aid? You know, the system itself should have

01:31:38.820 --> 01:31:43.460
[Amit Varma]: those safeguards in place and restrict the power of a person like that. And the problem

01:31:43.460 --> 01:31:47.980
[Amit Varma]: here isn't Narendra Modi per se. And this is perhaps the libertarian in me saying the

01:31:47.980 --> 01:31:54.140
[Guest]: problem is a coercive state. Yeah. And we have, there are institutions to check that

01:31:54.140 --> 01:31:58.540
[Guest]: power. There is the Supreme Court of India. There is a judiciary. Easy enough to capture

01:31:58.540 --> 01:32:03.020
[Amit Varma]: though, as we have seen, like you've pointed out, for example, that the judge who, you

01:32:03.020 --> 01:32:07.860
[Amit Varma]: know, let Amit Shah go in that acquitted Amit Shah in that case. Governor of Kerala. There

01:32:07.860 --> 01:32:14.940
[Guest]: you go. Yeah. The thing is, we have to remember that institutions are peopled by human beings

01:32:14.940 --> 01:32:22.580
[Guest]: and human beings are weak. Human beings, you made that point earlier, you know, human beings

01:32:22.580 --> 01:32:28.100
[Guest]: will respond to incentives and human beings will respond to threats. The best, we're looking

01:32:28.100 --> 01:32:32.740
[Guest]: at the United States of America, you know, the Republican Party is one of their great

01:32:32.740 --> 01:32:38.980
[Guest]: institutions and it has completely surrendered to Donald Trump. Every nation, every institution

01:32:38.980 --> 01:32:46.780
[Guest]: that is necessary for the competent functioning of government is ultimately run by human beings

01:32:46.780 --> 01:32:54.460
[Guest]: and the caliber of human beings that run it. Who in his right mind would want to take on

01:32:54.460 --> 01:32:59.060
[Guest]: the prime minister right now? Would, you know, if you're running an agency in the government,

01:32:59.060 --> 01:33:01.940
[Guest]: would you want to challenge the prime minister of authority? There are people who've done

01:33:01.940 --> 01:33:08.940
[Guest]: it. You know, let us remember when UPA was in power, there was a bureaucrat who challenged

01:33:08.940 --> 01:33:15.540
[Guest]: Robert Vadra and he found himself being transferred, relocated to some barren district. You know,

01:33:15.540 --> 01:33:19.920
[Guest]: this is not Modi alone who's done this. Modi is not unprecedented. You know, Modi is very

01:33:19.920 --> 01:33:25.420
[Guest]: much part of a tradition in India and the answer to this is the public protests. It

01:33:25.420 --> 01:33:29.020
[Guest]: is the people of India who've come out in the streets. It's not the institutions of

01:33:29.020 --> 01:33:34.140
[Guest]: India. The institutions of India have proven themselves to be weak and fragile. It is the

01:33:34.140 --> 01:33:41.460
[Guest]: ordinary people of India who've proven themselves to be powerful citizens. It is the constitution,

01:33:41.460 --> 01:33:47.060
[Guest]: is the values that animate the constitutions are finding expression in the protests across

01:33:47.060 --> 01:33:51.940
[Guest]: India, not in the institutions of India. So in that contest between the citizen and the

01:33:51.940 --> 01:33:57.260
[Guest]: state, of course, the state is more powerful, but the state's power is exhaustible, whereas

01:33:57.260 --> 01:34:02.140
[Guest]: the citizen's power, we'll have to see how far that will take us. You know, how it is

01:34:02.140 --> 01:34:06.760
[Guest]: impossible, I agree with you, to sustain people's protests of the kind that are taking place

01:34:06.760 --> 01:34:12.220
[Guest]: across India. So unfortunately, my answer to you is not going to be a hopeful one, because

01:34:12.220 --> 01:34:19.940
[Guest]: as much as I want to drag this on and find a way of, you know, convincing myself that

01:34:19.940 --> 01:34:26.220
[Guest]: we can, you know, that institutions will reign the prime minister in, we still are at the

01:34:26.220 --> 01:34:29.140
[Guest]: mercy of the better angels of Narendra Modi at the moment.

01:34:29.140 --> 01:34:33.420
[Guest]: Okay, that is the opposite of hopeful. What I mean, I just want to say that this doesn't

01:34:33.420 --> 01:34:38.980
[Guest]: necessarily indict the framers of our constitution or the founders of our republic. It just reveals

01:34:38.980 --> 01:34:46.020
[Guest]: that human beings ultimately are the people who run the show and the kind of country will

01:34:46.020 --> 01:34:52.060
[Guest]: be will depend on the caliber of the people who run the institutions upon which your country's

01:34:52.060 --> 01:34:53.060
[Guest]: performance depends.

01:34:53.060 --> 01:34:59.500
[Amit Varma]: I would say that I disagree with that. I mean, I agree that it is silly to blame the conception

01:34:59.500 --> 01:35:03.620
[Amit Varma]: or the constitution or the framers of the constitution in hindsight, because this stuff

01:35:03.620 --> 01:35:09.500
[Amit Varma]: looks obvious. But I think that, you know, if they sat down today to make a constitution,

01:35:09.500 --> 01:35:14.140
[Amit Varma]: knowing what is known today about incentives and the way people respond and understanding

01:35:14.140 --> 01:35:19.100
[Amit Varma]: public choice theory, they would definitely have designed a system that works far better

01:35:19.100 --> 01:35:24.340
[Amit Varma]: in terms of reigning state power and making many of these excesses, not so likely, but

01:35:24.340 --> 01:35:25.340
[Amit Varma]: my other...

01:35:25.340 --> 01:35:30.660
[Guest]: Many of the instructions yell down to the offices. For instance, we have heard a tape

01:35:30.660 --> 01:35:36.500
[Guest]: which was published by Cobra Post, I think, years ago, Amit Shah yelling instructions

01:35:36.500 --> 01:35:40.100
[Guest]: to the police officers in Gujarat to stalk a woman.

01:35:40.100 --> 01:35:42.300
[Amit Varma]: Because Sahib wanted it, you know.

01:35:42.300 --> 01:35:46.900
[Guest]: That was definitely illegal. There was no legal sanction for it. And the police was

01:35:46.900 --> 01:35:52.660
[Guest]: doing it because the Home Minister wanted it done. So I think had there been rules explicitly

01:35:52.660 --> 01:35:53.660
[Guest]: prohibiting...

01:35:53.660 --> 01:35:56.900
[Guest]: There are rules explicitly prohibiting the Home Minister from doing that, but yet he

01:35:56.900 --> 01:36:03.820
[Guest]: was able to do it. Power functions in a different way. And any number of rules can be written.

01:36:03.820 --> 01:36:09.100
[Guest]: They will not amount to much if people do not uphold them. Even if our constitution

01:36:09.100 --> 01:36:14.100
[Guest]: was revised and rewritten to take into account the conditions of today, I don't think they

01:36:14.100 --> 01:36:21.860
[Guest]: could reign in Modi. Because once you acquire power, it's very difficult to reign in power.

01:36:21.860 --> 01:36:26.260
[Guest]: And the only way to do that is... This is the reason I think Nehru is such an extraordinary

01:36:26.260 --> 01:36:31.460
[Guest]: figure because he had so much power at his disposal and he didn't abuse it.

01:36:31.460 --> 01:36:36.980
[Amit Varma]: I would still say that there are a lot of changes to the design of that conception and

01:36:36.980 --> 01:36:40.260
[Amit Varma]: not for a moment am I saying the constitution should be rewritten because if it is, it'll

01:36:40.260 --> 01:36:44.080
[Amit Varma]: become something far worse than what it already is. Both of us know that. And that would be

01:36:44.080 --> 01:36:49.180
[Amit Varma]: something to be very scared of. But what I would say is that within the design, you can

01:36:49.180 --> 01:36:55.220
[Amit Varma]: make things better. For example, the separation of powers between the executive and the legislature,

01:36:55.220 --> 01:36:59.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, and right now, if you look at what's happening in India, the legislature is completely

01:36:59.380 --> 01:37:04.860
[Amit Varma]: toothless. And if you look at what it is in the US, okay, Trump has gone out of control,

01:37:04.860 --> 01:37:08.400
[Amit Varma]: he's captured the Republican Party, blah, blah, there are many things to be moaned there.

01:37:08.400 --> 01:37:12.980
[Amit Varma]: But I would hold that Trump can do far less damage to the United States than Modi can

01:37:12.980 --> 01:37:17.380
[Amit Varma]: to India, because Modi has far more power here. And over there, the institutions are

01:37:17.380 --> 01:37:22.900
[Amit Varma]: still functioning, because of the way they were designed. But no, I would just say that

01:37:22.900 --> 01:37:28.460
[Guest]: the Parliament, unfortunately, has been reduced to a rubber stamp. And this process began

01:37:28.460 --> 01:37:33.820
[Guest]: again, a long time ago. And one of the things Modi has done, which people don't reflect

01:37:33.820 --> 01:37:39.460
[Guest]: on very much is he has converted BJP into a version of the Congress Party. The BJP was

01:37:39.460 --> 01:37:43.140
[Guest]: one of the few political parties in India that was actually internally democratic. The

01:37:43.140 --> 01:37:47.820
[Guest]: Prime Minister's own biography is a tribute to the democratic nature of the BJP. He was,

01:37:47.820 --> 01:37:53.740
[Guest]: after all, a lower caste tea seller from Gujarat, whose assent the party actually enabled. What

01:37:53.740 --> 01:37:59.060
[Guest]: he's done is he's destroyed the BJP, pretty much the way in which Mrs. Gandhi destroyed

01:37:59.060 --> 01:38:05.740
[Guest]: the Congress. He's destroyed the BJP's internal workings, and he has created a cult of personality

01:38:05.740 --> 01:38:11.860
[Guest]: unrivaled in India's history. The only equal is Mrs. Gandhi, but I think he's exceeded

01:38:11.860 --> 01:38:13.460
[Guest]: even her now.

01:38:13.460 --> 01:38:18.260
[Amit Varma]: I think he's a true successor to Mrs. Gandhi, first of all. And secondly, I would say that

01:38:18.260 --> 01:38:22.620
[Amit Varma]: in many ways, she was still worse than excesses of the emergency, which you have also written

01:38:22.620 --> 01:38:27.380
[Amit Varma]: about in your book, where we, for example, there were more people sterilized, there were

01:38:27.380 --> 01:38:33.380
[Amit Varma]: 15 times more people sterilized in India than done by the Nazis. Yeah, you know, and virtually

01:38:33.380 --> 01:38:38.780
[Amit Varma]: the entire opposition and the press was in prison, which is not yet the case here. We

01:38:38.780 --> 01:38:42.860
[Amit Varma]: are getting there. And what's happening in Kashmir is absolutely shocking and already

01:38:42.860 --> 01:38:46.900
[Amit Varma]: normalized. And, you know, we're recording this on Feb. 7. I don't know how much worse

01:38:46.900 --> 01:38:47.900
[Guest]: things will become.

01:38:47.900 --> 01:38:51.940
[Guest]: The cult of personality is certainly bigger than Indira Gandhi because the money, the

01:38:51.940 --> 01:38:57.820
[Guest]: kind of money and technology at Modi's disposal, but the abuse of power is nowhere as grotesque

01:38:57.820 --> 01:39:03.140
[Guest]: as it was during Mrs. Gandhi's reign. That is that is a point we must make. But what

01:39:03.140 --> 01:39:07.900
[Guest]: Modi has done is he has converted the BJP into a version of the Congress Party. He doesn't

01:39:07.900 --> 01:39:12.660
[Guest]: have children, so there's no fear of a dynasty, but there is an ideological dynasty. So, in

01:39:12.660 --> 01:39:17.100
[Guest]: time, I mentioned this in the book, we may look back on Modi as the moderate because

01:39:17.100 --> 01:39:22.500
[Guest]: his successor, if it's Amit Shah or Adityanath, are going to be infinitely more radical than

01:39:22.500 --> 01:39:25.540
[Guest]: he is. And this is the problem.

01:39:25.540 --> 01:39:29.860
[Amit Varma]: And this is a trend, as I mentioned earlier, in, you know, through the leaders of the Hindutva

01:39:29.860 --> 01:39:30.860
[Amit Varma]: movement.

01:39:30.860 --> 01:39:31.860
[Guest]: You go from bad to worse.

01:39:31.860 --> 01:39:35.700
[Amit Varma]: You go from bad to worse. My other question goes back to a point that you were making

01:39:35.700 --> 01:39:39.920
[Amit Varma]: earlier where you cited Raymond Aron talking in the context of Algeria, where he spoke

01:39:39.920 --> 01:39:44.540
[Amit Varma]: about passion and interests and how passion will always win out, which, of course, is

01:39:44.540 --> 01:39:50.580
[Amit Varma]: analogous to how the most ignorant people always show the most certitude. And the more

01:39:50.580 --> 01:39:55.380
[Amit Varma]: you know, the more you are full of doubt and the more intellectual humility you have.

01:39:55.380 --> 01:40:00.860
[Amit Varma]: So in that context of passions, what I find in India today and what gives me a lot of

01:40:00.860 --> 01:40:07.020
[Amit Varma]: despair is that all the political parties are catering to those passions. It's not just

01:40:07.020 --> 01:40:12.060
[Amit Varma]: that it's a BJP. You have, for example, Congress governments in various states like the Kamal

01:40:12.060 --> 01:40:16.660
[Amit Varma]: Nath government in Madhya Pradesh doing things for cow protection and so on and so forth,

01:40:16.660 --> 01:40:22.540
[Amit Varma]: the sort of soft Hindutva happening there. You have Kejriwal in Delhi and at one point

01:40:22.540 --> 01:40:26.860
[Amit Varma]: the Aam Aadmi Party seemed such a big hope in terms of a political movement erupting

01:40:26.860 --> 01:40:32.780
[Amit Varma]: out of a protest. And instead, what you find is that he has also stayed away from the Shaheen

01:40:32.780 --> 01:40:36.620
[Amit Varma]: Bagh issues in Delhi at the time of speaking. And obviously, the elections are just around

01:40:36.620 --> 01:40:40.140
[Amit Varma]: the corner. And by the time this says those will be out, but those don't have any bearing

01:40:40.140 --> 01:40:45.100
[Amit Varma]: on it. He's kept these protests at an arm's length and he doesn't want to piss off the

01:40:45.100 --> 01:40:49.940
[Amit Varma]: very people who are the base of the BJP, who the BJP has captured right now. So what he

01:40:49.940 --> 01:40:55.340
[Amit Varma]: is saying is that I am not necessarily against you guys or with Shaheen Bagh. I am just saying

01:40:55.340 --> 01:41:01.620
[Amit Varma]: vote for me for governance. A, does this worry you that all of the political party cater

01:41:01.620 --> 01:41:06.380
[Amit Varma]: to these negative passions which are leading us awry and which are dividing our society?

01:41:06.380 --> 01:41:11.500
[Amit Varma]: And B, is it also something you worry about that when a political party does emerge out

01:41:11.500 --> 01:41:15.900
[Amit Varma]: of these protests as the Aam Aadmi Party did out of an earlier protest, they will again

01:41:15.900 --> 01:41:22.260
[Amit Varma]: be prey to the incentives of politics and driven by the desire for power rather than

01:41:22.260 --> 01:41:28.220
[Guest]: out of any higher ideals? That's such a fascinating question. Let me

01:41:28.220 --> 01:41:34.460
[Guest]: just digest that question and give you an answer. We are at a point in our history where

01:41:34.460 --> 01:41:41.020
[Guest]: we can clear the stables because for the first time, we are witnessing a pan-Indian backlash

01:41:41.020 --> 01:41:48.340
[Guest]: against a prime minister who ended the coalition era. So this is a moment in which a pan-Indian

01:41:48.340 --> 01:41:55.300
[Guest]: political party could be born. But the existing political parties are completely bankrupt

01:41:55.300 --> 01:42:01.540
[Guest]: ideologically and ethically. And the trend of course again was set by the Congress Party.

01:42:01.540 --> 01:42:08.140
[Guest]: The obstacle to the rise of a pan-Indian political party is of course the Congress Party because

01:42:08.140 --> 01:42:14.580
[Guest]: it occupies the opposition. It lulls us into the false belief that there is an opposition

01:42:14.580 --> 01:42:19.980
[Guest]: party when in fact there isn't an opposition party. So I have been, wherever I've been

01:42:19.980 --> 01:42:24.100
[Guest]: going and speaking to people, I've been urging them not to vote for the Congress Party but

01:42:24.100 --> 01:42:31.140
[Guest]: to vote for a better alternative. If the Congress Party dies, we are more likely to see the

01:42:31.140 --> 01:42:35.100
[Guest]: emergence of a true political alternative to the BJP.

01:42:35.100 --> 01:42:38.420
[Amit Varma]: I don't want to interrupt you but wouldn't it also be the case that if the Gandhis were

01:42:38.420 --> 01:42:40.980
[Amit Varma]: somehow out of the way and their capture of the party ended?

01:42:40.980 --> 01:42:45.580
[Guest]: You needn't finish that question because I agree entirely with you. The Congress Party

01:42:45.580 --> 01:42:55.220
[Guest]: is like an army. It has excellent armory but it is presided over by an utterly corrupt

01:42:55.220 --> 01:43:01.260
[Guest]: general. You replace the general and you repurpose the army. You could do that but there is the

01:43:01.260 --> 01:43:06.380
[Guest]: fear that if that general goes, all the troops will be demoralized. Why don't you find a

01:43:06.380 --> 01:43:11.260
[Guest]: better general who can actually mobilize them, who can give them hope again?

01:43:11.260 --> 01:43:14.620
[Guest]: There are people in the Congress Party who can do that. I was in southern India and I

01:43:14.620 --> 01:43:21.420
[Guest]: spoke to a former minister who is still a member of parliament and he and I have had

01:43:21.420 --> 01:43:27.420
[Guest]: very intense arguments in the past and we had very heated arguments but he came up to

01:43:27.420 --> 01:43:32.340
[Guest]: me this time and he said to me, I agree entirely with you and I would like to see this family

01:43:32.340 --> 01:43:39.500
[Guest]: gone. This is a man who's been appointed to his job by the family. This is a man who owes

01:43:39.500 --> 01:43:43.140
[Guest]: his career to the family and he said, but I care more about the country than I do about

01:43:43.140 --> 01:43:44.140
[Amit Varma]: my own career.

01:43:44.140 --> 01:43:47.380
[Amit Varma]: This is, by the way, something other Congress leaders have said to me in private but they

01:43:47.380 --> 01:43:48.380
[Amit Varma]: will never say it in public.

01:43:48.380 --> 01:43:52.660
[Guest]: They will never say it in public. Instead, he was urging me to amplify that message to

01:43:52.660 --> 01:43:58.740
[Guest]: say that go after the family. We need to get rid of them. He said, for a year, there'll

01:43:58.740 --> 01:44:02.660
[Guest]: be chaos in the party. There'll be demands to bring the family back but the family must

01:44:02.660 --> 01:44:08.540
[Guest]: go and they must be a new leader and, you know, Congress will survive the exit of the

01:44:08.540 --> 01:44:14.940
[Guest]: Gandhi family and it is now, I think, in the national interest for the family to leave

01:44:14.940 --> 01:44:16.220
[Guest]: this party.

01:44:16.220 --> 01:44:22.420
[Guest]: This party can no longer be an instrument for the realization of the personal desires

01:44:22.420 --> 01:44:27.540
[Guest]: and dreams of one family. It has to be an instrument for the reclamation of India. So

01:44:27.540 --> 01:44:32.700
[Guest]: there is already an existing infrastructure. You can repurpose this army to become a true

01:44:32.700 --> 01:44:38.980
[Guest]: opposition party. So I would say if you can't vote against Congress party, at least join

01:44:38.980 --> 01:44:45.540
[Guest]: the Congress party and clamor for the defenestration of the Gandhi family, clamor for a new leadership.

01:44:45.540 --> 01:44:50.860
[Guest]: If you want to rescue India, that project is the project of a generation and it will

01:44:50.860 --> 01:44:55.300
[Guest]: begin – you will have to begin by rescuing the Congress party and rescuing the Congress

01:44:55.300 --> 01:45:02.780
[Guest]: party means removing the Gandhis. Please remove this family. This family is now the principal

01:45:02.780 --> 01:45:09.380
[Guest]: obstacle. If India goes to a point of no return, a massive share of the responsibility, blame,

01:45:09.380 --> 01:45:14.340
[Guest]: will have to be shouldered by this family. We are at a point when we can go down the

01:45:14.340 --> 01:45:20.740
[Guest]: route of Yugoslavia and congressmen are still unable to raise their voices and say that

01:45:20.740 --> 01:45:25.780
[Guest]: please leave, please give the Congress party back to the people of India so they can use

01:45:25.780 --> 01:45:31.100
[Guest]: it as a vehicle for true secularism, for true liberalism. There's nobody willing to say

01:45:31.100 --> 01:45:35.500
[Guest]: that, nobody willing to risk his or her career. They did that when Sonia Gandhi became the

01:45:35.500 --> 01:45:38.820
[Guest]: leader of the Congress party, Sangma and Sharath Pawar.

01:45:38.820 --> 01:45:39.820
[Guest]: And look what happened to them.

01:45:39.820 --> 01:45:42.900
[Guest]: And look what happened to them. They, you know, they came back into the fold.

01:45:42.900 --> 01:45:46.580
[Amit Varma]: I actually wrote a column about this about, you know, looking at it from a perspective

01:45:46.580 --> 01:45:51.300
[Amit Varma]: of game theory, that it's very suboptimal for someone to be the first to speak out.

01:45:51.300 --> 01:45:55.540
[Amit Varma]: You would rather free roll and wait for other people to rebel and then kind of ride the

01:45:55.540 --> 01:45:56.540
[Guest]: wave.

01:45:56.540 --> 01:46:00.620
[Guest]: But, you know, that momentum, in order for that momentum to come about, you need someone

01:46:00.620 --> 01:46:06.980
[Guest]: to make that voice. I imagine if Shashi Tharoor made that speech tomorrow. Imagine if someone

01:46:06.980 --> 01:46:12.020
[Guest]: like that, there are people, I don't want to name people because I've had private conversations

01:46:12.020 --> 01:46:17.340
[Guest]: with a lot of people. I think they're waiting for that first spark. I remember I, this is

01:46:17.340 --> 01:46:22.500
[Guest]: perhaps not the right analogy, the right story, but I remember watching, I remember reading

01:46:22.500 --> 01:46:29.020
[Guest]: about Romania, you know, Nicolae Ceausescu was so powerful that, you know, he came back

01:46:29.020 --> 01:46:32.900
[Guest]: from a tour of the Middle East and he was giving a speech in the public square and it

01:46:32.900 --> 01:46:35.660
[Guest]: took one person to make a noise against him.

01:46:35.660 --> 01:46:40.380
[Guest]: And eventually the entire crowd yelled against him and he had to take a helicopter from the

01:46:40.380 --> 01:46:43.220
[Guest]: roof of that building and within four days he was gone.

01:46:43.220 --> 01:46:47.340
[Amit Varma]: That's what the sociologist Timur Kuran calls a preference cascade, where earlier you have

01:46:47.340 --> 01:46:50.540
[Amit Varma]: preference falsification and no one is speaking up because they're scared. They're the only

01:46:50.540 --> 01:46:54.580
[Amit Varma]: one who feel that way and they're scared to speak up. But once one guy speaks up, there's

01:46:54.580 --> 01:46:59.820
[Amit Varma]: a cascade and then things change very fast. Except that I worry that in India, the preferences

01:46:59.820 --> 01:47:01.700
[Guest]: are sort of in the wrong direction at the moment.

01:47:01.700 --> 01:47:05.680
[Guest]: Well, there is an entire category, there's an entire class of people who will happily

01:47:05.680 --> 01:47:10.460
[Guest]: have a monarchy in India if it's run by the Gandhi family because they genuinely believe

01:47:10.460 --> 01:47:14.460
[Guest]: that the Gandhi family are protectors of Indian secularism. There are genuinely people and

01:47:14.460 --> 01:47:19.100
[Guest]: you cannot reason with them. You cannot show them proof that, hang on, this is what Rahul

01:47:19.100 --> 01:47:23.900
[Guest]: Gandhi did, this is what Rajiv Gandhi did, this is what Indira Gandhi did, this is what

01:47:23.900 --> 01:47:27.460
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh did when he was Prime Minister. You can't talk to them, you can't reason with

01:47:27.460 --> 01:47:33.340
[Guest]: them because they are completely lost in their devotions to the Gandhi family. Those people

01:47:33.340 --> 01:47:38.900
[Guest]: you cannot convert and our energies are finite. We shouldn't squander them on trying to convert

01:47:38.900 --> 01:47:45.100
[Guest]: them. We should rather direct them at people who might be able to create an alternative

01:47:45.100 --> 01:47:51.060
[Guest]: Congress party. And I, to the extent that there are any listeners in the Congress party,

01:47:51.060 --> 01:47:55.500
[Guest]: I would urge them, please write to your MP, write to your leader and tell them to speak

01:47:55.500 --> 01:47:59.420
[Guest]: up against the Gandhi's. Join the Congress party, take up primary membership of the Congress

01:47:59.420 --> 01:48:05.540
[Guest]: party and call for elections, call for democratic elections within the Congress party. That

01:48:05.540 --> 01:48:11.260
[Amit Varma]: is one source of hope. I think any Congress member who's just heard this has thought to

01:48:11.260 --> 01:48:15.340
[Amit Varma]: himself, I'll join the cascade, but I'm not going to be the first guy to raise my hand.

01:48:15.340 --> 01:48:19.780
[Amit Varma]: We have like 10 minutes left to wrap this up. And normally what I do is at the end of

01:48:19.780 --> 01:48:23.420
[Amit Varma]: my episode, I ask people about what gives them hope and what gives them despair. But

01:48:23.420 --> 01:48:27.780
[Amit Varma]: you've spoken about that for all of this episode. Those have almost been the two principal points

01:48:27.780 --> 01:48:32.860
[Amit Varma]: of our discussion. And I usually begin my episode by asking people to trace their personal

01:48:32.860 --> 01:48:38.740
[Amit Varma]: journeys and there wasn't kind of enough of that. So let's sort of end on a note of, you

01:48:38.740 --> 01:48:42.780
[Amit Varma]: know, okay, not, I won't ask you mundane details of how do you earn a living or where do you

01:48:42.780 --> 01:48:47.080
[Amit Varma]: live or what do you do? But what I would actually be very interested in, and I'm sure my listeners

01:48:47.080 --> 01:48:52.860
[Amit Varma]: as well, are what are your dominant intellectual influences? Like, are there any thinkers or

01:48:52.860 --> 01:48:57.000
[Amit Varma]: books that changed the way you think about the world? If you had to recommend say three

01:48:57.000 --> 01:49:01.620
[Amit Varma]: or five books to my listeners that you feel they must go out and read, what would they

01:49:01.620 --> 01:49:03.660
[Guest]: be? Give me a sense of that.

01:49:03.660 --> 01:49:15.500
[Guest]: Right. The thinkers who've profoundly influenced me are Gandhi, Nehru in India. And abroad,

01:49:15.500 --> 01:49:23.340
[Guest]: I've been massively influenced by movements abroad. I've been, I've followed Eastern European

01:49:23.340 --> 01:49:31.100
[Guest]: politics for a long time and I've taken, I've found that to be a fount of tremendous hope.

01:49:31.100 --> 01:49:38.760
[Guest]: But I think we have in India, there is such an untapped source of wisdom and inspiration

01:49:38.760 --> 01:49:45.380
[Guest]: in India. And I constantly look to parts of India that are neglected. I look to South

01:49:45.380 --> 01:49:52.780
[Guest]: India, I look to Eastern India and it's, I would say that every day I wake up and find

01:49:52.780 --> 01:49:59.100
[Guest]: myself profoundly ignorant because I discover things that I didn't know before. And often

01:49:59.100 --> 01:50:05.460
[Guest]: when you acquire knowledge by reading, you think you have gained an insight that allows

01:50:05.460 --> 01:50:11.420
[Guest]: you to disregard other insights. And it's a battle with yourself to reign your own arrogance

01:50:11.420 --> 01:50:16.700
[Guest]: in to say that, no, no, no, I don't know enough. Let me hear the other side. You know, John

01:50:16.700 --> 01:50:22.820
[Guest]: Stuart Mill says that even a lie should be allowed to be aired in public because there

01:50:22.820 --> 01:50:28.860
[Guest]: are two utilities. One is that if you listen to the opposing perspective, it'll challenge

01:50:28.860 --> 01:50:35.200
[Guest]: your own belief and you'll be able to challenge it. You'll be able to sharpen your own argument.

01:50:35.200 --> 01:50:38.660
[Guest]: But the other utility is that if it's a lie, then it will be heard by people and people

01:50:38.660 --> 01:50:42.580
[Guest]: will be able to reject it anyway. So I've been trying very much to listen to opposing

01:50:42.580 --> 01:50:47.660
[Guest]: perspectives. I've been trying to read people whom I disagree with profoundly, but coming

01:50:47.660 --> 01:50:55.500
[Guest]: to the more precise question of the books that really affected me, I read very eclectically.

01:50:55.500 --> 01:51:01.420
[Guest]: I read everything. Most of my time is spent reading. I will read anything. I'll read a

01:51:01.420 --> 01:51:06.060
[Guest]: report on agriculture. I'll read a 500 page report. I may not retain all the information,

01:51:06.060 --> 01:51:11.700
[Guest]: but I'll read it. But the book that really affected me in a way that I didn't think books

01:51:11.700 --> 01:51:15.980
[Guest]: would, you know, I had a physical reaction to the book, was V. S. Ninepole's An Area

01:51:15.980 --> 01:51:21.620
[Guest]: of Darkness. People say this book has changed my life. It didn't change my life. I read

01:51:21.620 --> 01:51:27.020
[Guest]: it at a time in life where I had certain beliefs. I was quite certain that I was secularist.

01:51:27.020 --> 01:51:34.140
[Guest]: I wasn't going to, you know, become a votary of religious nationalism. No way. But it spoke

01:51:34.140 --> 01:51:38.740
[Guest]: to me in a way that no book before had. I had a very physical reaction. I had to put

01:51:38.740 --> 01:51:43.140
[Guest]: the book down several times because nobody had written about India that way. And it was

01:51:43.140 --> 01:51:51.540
[Guest]: only 190 pages. And then I read Wounded Civilization by V. S. Ninepole. That also had a profound

01:51:51.540 --> 01:51:57.780
[Guest]: effect on me. Not as profound as An Area of Darkness, but it really moved me. So these

01:51:57.780 --> 01:52:03.780
[Guest]: are the two books I would recommend to anybody wanting to understand India. Whether you're

01:52:03.780 --> 01:52:08.680
[Guest]: a secularist, whether you're a Hindu nationalist, whatever your ideological belief, read those

01:52:08.680 --> 01:52:14.500
[Guest]: books. Read V. S. Ninepole because I cannot think of another writer, not even Orwell,

01:52:14.500 --> 01:52:22.060
[Guest]: who conveyed truth with such clarity. Beyond Ninepole, the book that I would very much

01:52:22.060 --> 01:52:28.780
[Guest]: recommend is The Discovery of India by Nehru. It's an extraordinary work. It's not a work

01:52:28.780 --> 01:52:33.420
[Guest]: of history. It's not a work of scholarship, but it tells you about the calibre of our

01:52:33.420 --> 01:52:34.420
[Guest]: leadership.

01:52:34.420 --> 01:52:38.980
[Guest]: It lays out the vision of the world, so to say.

01:52:38.980 --> 01:52:43.940
[Guest]: It shows you how sophisticated our inaugural prime minister was, what an extraordinary

01:52:43.940 --> 01:52:49.020
[Guest]: man he was, what an extraordinary man of learning he was, and what a capacious vision he had.

01:52:49.020 --> 01:52:52.840
[Amit Varma]: And it's striking that you should say this when in your book, there is actually a tremendous

01:52:52.840 --> 01:52:56.980
[Amit Varma]: amount of criticism of Nehru. And yet he is one of the people who's inspired you and is

01:52:56.980 --> 01:53:02.180
[Amit Varma]: a hero to you, which indicates, like, I don't want to flatter you, but the kind of minds

01:53:02.180 --> 01:53:08.060
[Amit Varma]: who I like to read and follow are people who are open to a multiplicity of views on a single

01:53:08.060 --> 01:53:14.700
[Amit Varma]: subject and sort of, you know, who don't take, like, today the world looks at Nehru so simplistically.

01:53:14.700 --> 01:53:19.740
[Amit Varma]: He's either very, very good or very, very bad. And it's sort of important to know that.

01:53:19.740 --> 01:53:25.420
[Guest]: I think in Nehru's personality was reflected all the multiplicity of India. And I find

01:53:25.420 --> 01:53:31.280
[Guest]: him to be, I admire him immensely. I mean, one shouldn't use the word hero loosely, but

01:53:31.280 --> 01:53:36.460
[Guest]: if I had a hero, I think it would be Nehru. I admire that man immensely. And which is

01:53:36.460 --> 01:53:43.820
[Guest]: precisely why I find the flaws so dispiriting and so galling. And those are the three books

01:53:43.820 --> 01:53:48.420
[Guest]: I've recommended, but other books I'm, you know, there are so many books that shape one's

01:53:48.420 --> 01:53:53.340
[Guest]: personality that shapes one's thinking. There are so many to single one out would be to

01:53:53.340 --> 01:53:59.220
[Guest]: omit others. But if you're looking for recommendations, I would say Malevolent Republic is a pretty

01:53:59.220 --> 01:54:05.100
[Amit Varma]: good book. I second that for all my listeners. There are actually a couple of areas in your

01:54:05.100 --> 01:54:09.580
[Amit Varma]: book that I slightly disagree with, like your characterization of liberalization, where

01:54:09.580 --> 01:54:13.460
[Amit Varma]: I think you find a causal link between the good things P. V. Narasimha Rao did and the

01:54:13.460 --> 01:54:17.060
[Amit Varma]: bad things and I don't quite agree with that, but we'll talk about it in some other episode.

01:54:17.060 --> 01:54:20.980
[Amit Varma]: Sure. Kapil, thanks so much. It's been an absolute privilege having you on the show.

01:54:20.980 --> 01:54:25.100
[Guest]: It has been an honour for me. Thank you, Amit.

